	\chapter{Introduction}
	\label{chap:introduction}
	
	\section{Background and Motivation}
	
	Dental radiography continues to be a fundamental tool in contemporary dental diagnostics, offering crucial visual data for identifying abnormalities and disease, guiding treatment planning, and tracking changes in oral health over time. \cite{white_pharoah_radiology}. The interpretation of dental radiographs including panoramic, periapical, and bitewing images requires specialized expertise to identify subtle abnormalities such as caries, loss of periodontal bone, periapical lesions, and fractures. Although not comprehensive compared to other imaging modalities, Peri-apical dental radiographs are the most commonly used diagnostic imaging modality in dentistry in resource limited countries, as they are the least expensive yet still provide an invaluable tool for accurate dental diagnosis. Figure ~\ref{fig:radiographs_samples} presents examples of peri-apical radiographs along with the associated clinical interpretations, which inform decisions about the appropriate course of patient management.  Despite this critical need, the accuracy and consistency of radiographic interpretation can vary significantly depending on the clinician's experience, workload, and access to reference materials. This variability poses particular challenges in resource constrained settings where specialist oversight is limited and general practitioners must make critical diagnostic decisions independently. Accurate diagnosis and timely treatment planning are essential to prevent disease progression and long term complications, yet dental diseases remain among the most prevalent non communicable conditions worldwide \cite{who_oral_health, world2024global}.
	
	The integration of Artificial Intelligence (AI) into dentistry has accelerated over the past decade, with remarkable progress in medical image analysis across multiple domains including radiology, pathology, and ophthalmology \cite{litjens2017survey, wani2020deep, schwendicke2020artificial}. Deep learning models, particularly convolutional neural networks (CNNs), have demonstrated high accuracy in tasks such as caries detection, periodontal bone loss assessment and pathology identification in dental radiographic images, with reported accuracies often exceeding 0.80 on benchmark datasets \cite{lee2019deep, peerj2024caries}. Recent commercial dental AI products such as Diagnocat and Pearl AI leverage computer vision to assist clinicians with preliminary radiographic analysis \cite{davis2021dentist, dorr2023ai}. At the same time, emerging multimodal dental datasets combining cone-beam CT (CBCT), panoramic, and periapical radiographs with associated clinical information have created new opportunities for AI systems that reason across multiple imaging modalities and patient contexts \cite{Zhang2024MultimodalDental}.
	
	Parallel to advances in medical imaging, Large Language Models (LLMs) have emerged as powerful tools for natural language understanding and generation, enabling automated clinical documentation, reasoning over patient history, and conversational decision support \cite{thirunavukarasu2023large}. The convergence of these technologies, vision models and language models has given rise to multimodal AI systems capable of processing and reasoning over multiple data types simultaneously \cite{huang2023multimodal}. In theory, such systems could mimic the holistic approach of a human dentist, who integrates visual evidence from radiographs with contextual information from patient history, symptoms, and clinical notes to arrive at a diagnosis and formulate a treatment plan. This represents a significant leap from traditional single-modality AI tools, promising more sophisticated and context-aware clinical decision support.
	
