	\subsection{Challenges in Current AI-Based Dental Systems}
	
	Despite these promising advances, most existing AI models for dental imaging operate as narrow, task-specific classifiers with limited ability to incorporate patient history, clinical guidelines, or broader textual context \cite{peerj2024caries}. Several critical limitations persist in current dental diagnostic systems that hinder their real world adoption and clinical utility.
	
	\textbf{Lack of Multimodal Integration and Contextual Reasoning:} Existing systems primarily analyze radiographic images in isolation, ignoring valuable contextual information from patient history, clinical notes, and previous examinations. Effective clinical decision making requires synthesis of visual findings with patient-specific factors such as age, medical conditions, symptoms, and risk factors. This limitation reduces their usefulness as comprehensive clinical decision support tools, especially in real world settings where diagnostic decisions depend on both radiographic findings and contextual information \cite{White01121999}.
	
	\textbf{Black-Box Nature and Lack of Explainability:} Many deep learning models operate as "black boxes," producing predictions without transparent reasoning or explicit reference to clinical knowledge \cite{holzinger2017we}. This lack of interpretability poses significant challenges in clinical environments, where accountability, explainability, and adherence to established guidelines are essential for clinician trust and patient safety. When outputs lack grounding (Figure ~\ref{fig:blak_box_challenge}) in established clinical knowledge, clinician confidence in AI-generated recommendations diminishes significantly.
	
	\textbf{Hallucination and Knowledge Grounding Issues:} Conventional multimodal AI systems often rely solely on model parameters learned from training data, making them susceptible to factual hallucinations, plausible sounding but incorrect or unsubstantiated recommendations \cite{ji2023survey}. Most AI models are trained to predict pathologies based on pattern recognition without explicit reference to clinical guidelines or evidence-based literature. In the medical domain, such limitations are particularly concerning, as incorrect or unsupported recommendations may lead to inappropriate clinical decisions and potentially compromise patient safety.
	
	\textbf{Limited Adaptability to Local Contexts and Regional Guidelines:} Pre-trained models are typically developed using datasets from high-resource settings (predominantly North America, Europe, or East Asia) and may not generalize well to populations with different disease profiles, radiographic equipment quality, or healthcare protocols. Clinical guidelines also vary across regions; treatment protocols are influenced by local healthcare policies, resource availability, and population specific disease patterns \cite{Rokhshad2025, schwendicke2022ai_global}. Most existing AI systems are trained and evaluated using datasets and guidelines from high-income countries, limiting their applicability in low and middle income settings. As a result, these systems may recommend treatments that are impractical or unavailable in resource constrained environments.
	
