	\subsection{The Urgent Need in Resource-Constrained Settings}
	
	These challenges are particularly acute in countries such as Tanzania, where the oral health burden is substantial and access to quality dental care remains severely limited. Tanzania faces a critical shortage of oral health personnel, with a dentist-to-population ratio of approximately 1:360,000, far below the World Health Organization's recommended ratio of 1:7,500 \cite{Edward2024OralHealthTZ}. Oral health is widely neglected in the healthcare system, with significant gaps in infrastructure, uneven geographic distribution of dental services, and fragmented access to evidence-based oral healthcare \cite{Edward2024OralHealthTZ}.
	
	In such contexts, dental professionals including recent graduates, interns, and general practitioners often operate with minimal specialist support in rural or under resourced clinics, managing complex cases with heavy patient loads and limited access to specialist consultations \cite{tanzania_oral_health_policy}. Diagnostic variability is common, particularly in training or high volume settings, where clinicians must balance radiographic interpretation with other clinical responsibilities. This creates an urgent demand for reliable, explainable AI support systems that can provide consistent, evidence based diagnostic assistance and reduce the cognitive burden on clinicians \cite{White1996DecisionSupport}.
	
	Furthermore, clinical guidelines and treatment protocols in Tanzania must consider local disease prevalence (e.g., high fluorosis prevalence in certain regions, e.g Arusha), medication accessibility, resource constraints, and healthcare policies that may differ substantially from international standards. Most existing AI systems fail to account for such local clinical guidelines or resource constraints, limiting their practical applicability and adoption in these critical settings.
	
	\subsection{The Promise of Retrieval-Augmented Generation in Dental AI}
	
	Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) has recently emerged as a promising paradigm for bridging the gap between powerful but opaque language models and the stringent reliability requirements of clinical care \cite{lewis2020retrieval}. Unlike traditional prompt-response language models that rely solely on memorized training data, RAG systems dynamically retrieve relevant information from external knowledge bases before generating outputs, integrating semantic retrieval over vetted knowledge sources directly into the generation process (Figure ~\ref{fig:RAG_flow}).
	
	Recent developments in radiology indicate that RAG can substantially reduce hallucinations, improve adherence of model outputs to institutional protocols, and boost the safety and accuracy of locally hosted language models by connecting them to validated guideline repositories at inference time \cite{Wada2025RAGRadiology}. Furthermore, evidence shows that models enhanced with RAG can eliminate dangerous hallucinations, operate efficiently on local, on-premise hardware, and maintain alignment with evidence based practices capabilities that are crucial for implementation in hospitals with limited computational capacity and scarce specialist staff \cite{Wada2025RAGRadiology}, which is a common context for many hospitals in Tanzania.
	
	In the context of dental diagnostics, applying this paradigm to dental radiograph analysis offers a compelling way to build systems that combine image-based feature extraction with context-aware, knowledge-grounded reasoning over patient history and clinical guidelines. A RAG-enhanced multimodal system offers several transformative advantages:
	
	\textbf{Evidence-Based Reasoning and Reduced Hallucination:} By retrieving clinical guidelines, treatment protocols, and peer reviewed literature relevant to each case, the system can ground its diagnostic and treatment recommendations in authoritative sources. This ensures alignment with established best practices, reduces factual hallucinations, and provides clinicians with traceable evidence for each suggestion, directly addressing the black-box limitation of current systems.
	
	\textbf{Transparency and Explainability:} By explicitly citing retrieved documents, the system transforms from an opaque predictor into an explainable decision support tool. Clinicians can review the source materials, assess the relevance of retrieved evidence, and make informed decisions about whether to accept or modify AI-generated recommendations. This transparency is essential for building trust and enabling adoption in clinical practice.
	
	\textbf{Adaptability to Regional Guidelines and Contexts:} The knowledge base can be customized to include country specific protocols (e.g., Tanzanian Ministry of Health dental guidelines) alongside international standards (e.g., American Dental Association, World Health Organization). This enables the system to provide contextually appropriate recommendations that consider local resource constraints, disease patterns, and healthcare policies, a critical requirement for deployment in diverse clinical settings.
	
	\textbf{Continuous Knowledge Updates:} Unlike static models that require retraining to incorporate new information, RAG systems can be updated simply by adding new documents to the knowledge base. This allows the system to stay current with evolving clinical guidelines, emerging research, and regional protocol changes without expensive and time consuming model retraining.
	
