	\subsection{Motivation for This Research}
	
	This thesis is driven by the intersection of three key factors: (1) the clinical need for better diagnostic support in dentistry, particularly in underserved settings; (2) the technological advancements offered by multimodal AI and RAG technique; and (3) the persistent shortcomings of current solutions in providing trustworthy, knowledge grounded reasoning. The demand for reliable and explainable AI support is especially pressing in resource limited healthcare environments, where general practitioners, dental interns, and clinicians in rural clinics are tasked with handling complex cases despite having limited access to specialists and only partial access to clinical guidelines \cite{Edward2024OralHealthTZ}.
	
	By designing a RAG-based multimodal system focused on dental radiograph interpretation, this research intends to narrow the gap between general purpose AI tools and the specific needs of clinical dental practice. The system is conceived with the Tanzanian dental care landscape in mind, where a high patient-to-dentist ratio, scarce specialist services in rural regions, and the central role of dental interns and general practitioners collectively generate a strong need for dependable decision support tools. At the same time, the modular system architecture and flexible knowledge base design allow the framework to be adapted and deployed in other geographical and clinical contexts.
	
	The ultimate objective is to develop an AI assistant that is trustworthy, transparent, and suitable for clinical integration, and that augments rather than replaces human clinical expertise. Knowledge grounded AI systems capable of delivering consistent, evidence based radiographic assessments and treatment recommendations could improve diagnostic accuracy, decrease variability in clinical decisions, support standardized care, and assist less experienced clinicians \cite{White1996DecisionSupport}. By supporting continuous updates of the knowledge base to incorporate evolving clinical guidelines and country specific protocols, the proposed system aims to provide a scalable and adaptable solution for AI-assisted dental diagnostics, thereby promoting more equitable access to high quality oral healthcare, especially in resource constrained settings.
	
	
