	\section{Problem Statement and Research Gap}
	
	Dental radiographs are central to the diagnosis and treatment planning of caries, periodontal disease, periapical pathology, and other oral conditions, yet their interpretation remains highly dependent on clinician expertise, leading to variability in diagnostic quality \cite{white_pharoah_radiology,White01121999}. Recent systematic reviews demonstrate that deep learning models can achieve high sensitivity and specificity for tasks such as caries detection, with performance approaching or exceeding clinical thresholds in controlled settings \cite{Dashti2024DLCariesUmbrella,Arzani2025AICariesUmbrella,MADANKUMAR20261}. However, these systems are predominantly unimodal and task-specific, focusing on isolated predictions (e.g., lesion presence on individual teeth) while offering limited support for comprehensive clinical decision making that must integrate radiographic findings with patient history, symptoms, and treatment protocols \cite{litjens2017survey,lee2019deep,schwendicke2020artificial}.
	
	Although still far from incomprehensive, multi-modal dental datasets combining radiographs with clinical information are beginning to emerge, illustrating potential for systems that reason jointly over images and text \cite{huang2024multimodal_dental}. Nevertheless, most current pipelines remain black-box predictors providing little explanation or explicit linkage to clinical guidelines, raising concerns about transparency and trust in clinical environments \cite{holzinger2017we,schwendicke2022ai_global}. Large language models (LLMs) and multimodal foundation models have shown strong performance in medical question answering and report generation, but they can hallucinate facts and generate plausible sounding yet clinically incorrect statements when not grounded in trusted sources \cite{thirunavukarasu2023large,ji2023survey,chatbots_Rajesh_2024}. These risks are particularly problematic in safety critical domains such as radiographic diagnosis, where erroneous recommendations can adversely affect patient outcomes and undermine clinician confidence \cite{Rokhshad2025}.
	
	In dentistry, clinical decision support systems (CDSS) have been discussed for decades, yet adoption remains limited and many systems are rule-based, narrow in scope, or technically outdated \cite{White1996DecisionSupport,inchingolo2025ai_dentistry_review}. Recent reviews emphasize that AI-based diagnostic tools can enhance consistency and efficiency but also highlight gaps in integration with clinical workflows, explainability, and alignment with current guidelines \cite{inchingolo2025ai_dentistry_review,schwendicke2020artificial}. These challenges are magnified in low and middle income countries where oral health remains a neglected priority despite high disease burden \cite{who_oral_health,world2024global}. Tanzania, for instance, faces severe shortage of oral health personnel, with dentist to population ratios far below international recommendations and substantial unmet need for basic diagnostic and treatment services \cite{Edward2024OralHealthTZ,tanzania_oral_health_policy}. In such settings, dental interns, general practitioners, and clinicians in rural facilities must frequently interpret radiographs and formulate treatment plans with limited specialist supervision and fragmented access to updated clinical guidelines.
	
	Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) has emerged as a promising paradigm for improving reliability and factual grounding of LLM-based systems by coupling generative models with explicit retrieval from curated knowledge sources at inference time \cite{lewis2020retrieval,ji2023survey}. In radiology, early evidence suggests RAG enhanced local LLMs can substantially reduce hallucinations, align responses with institutional protocols, and improve perceived safety and quality of outputs \cite{Wada2025RAGRadiology,chatbots_Rajesh_2024}. However, there is limited systematic work applying RAG to dental radiograph interpretation in a way that \\
	(i) jointly exploits image derived features and patient context, \\
	(ii) retrieves region and resource specific guideline knowledge, and \\
	(iii) produces transparent, knowledge-grounded diagnostic impressions tailored to settings such as Tanzania. \\
	This lack of a domain-specific, multimodal, and knowledge-grounded architecture for dental radiographs constitutes the critical research gap this thesis addresses.
	
