	\section{Scope and Limitations}
	This thesis focuses on the design, implementation, and evaluation of a RAG-based multimodal system for dental radiograph analysis, diagnosis, and treatment recommendation, with particular emphasis on architectural patterns, component integration, and deployment considerations for resource-constrained settings.
	
	\subsection{Scope of the Study}
	
	The scope encompasses the following dimensions:
	
	\begin{itemize}
		\item \textbf{Radiographic Modalities:} Analysis is limited to periapical radiographs, reflecting their widespread use in everyday dental practice, greater availability in open datasets, and diagnostic utility for highly prevalent conditions including dental caries, periodontal bone loss, periapical pathology, and tooth fractures \cite{white_pharoah_radiology,huang2024multimodal_dental,lee2019deep,schwendicke2020artificial}. The system architecture is designed to be extensible to other diagnostic modalities (e.g., panoramic, bitewing, CBCT) with minimal modification, though such extensions are not implemented or evaluated in this work.
		
		\item \textbf{Knowledge Base Construction:} A curated knowledge base is constructed comprising: \\
		(a) the Tanzanian Standard Treatment Guidelines (STG) from the Ministry of Health, serving as the primary regional clinical reference; \\
		(b) international guidelines from the World Health Organization; \\
		(c) peer reviewed dental literature excerpts relevant to common dental pathologies \cite{world2024global,Edward2024OralHealthTZ,tanzania_oral_health_policy}. The knowledge base is optimized for semantic retrieval through systematic evaluation of chunking strategies, embedding models (nomic-embed-text, mxbai-embed-large, MedEmbed), and indexing approaches.
		
		\item \textbf{Clinical Functions:} The system implements three core clinical capabilities: \\
		(a) preliminary diagnosis generation based on radiographic findings integrated with patient clinical context (patient's clinical history and current clinical complain); \\
		(b) evidence-based treatment recommendations explicitly grounded in retrieved clinical guidelines; \\
		(c) citation provision referencing specific page numbers and sections from source documents (e.g., "STG Tanzania, page 385") to enable clinician verification and support explainability.
		
		\item \textbf{Multimodal Integration Architecture:} The system implements a sequential pipeline architecture comprising three stages: \\
		(a) vision analysis for radiographic feature extraction and structured finding generation; \\
		(b) knowledge retrieval based on clinical context and vision findings; \\
		(c) clinical reasoning synthesis combining patient history, vision findings, and retrieved guidelines. The architecture emphasizes modular component separation with well defined interfaces, enabling independent substitution of models at each stage.
		
		\item \textbf{Multi-Provider Model Support:} The system integrates and evaluates a comprehensive set of vision models: \\
		(a) local models: LLaVA 7B/13B (Ollama), Gemma3 4B/12B (Ollama), BiomedCLIP (open clip), Florence-2 (HuggingFace); \\
		(b) cloud models: GPT-4V (OpenAI), Claude 3.5 Sonnet (Anthropic), Groq Llama vision models, Gemini 1.5/2.0 (Google). \\
		For clinical reasoning, the system supports five LLM providers: Ollama (local), OpenAI, Anthropic, Groq, and Google Gemini, enabling comparative analysis of performance, cost, and deployment flexibility across provider combinations.
		
		\item \textbf{Evaluation Methodology:} Evaluation encompasses multiple dimensions: \\
		(a) vision model comparative analysis measuring inference speed, resource utilization (RAM, disk), model-reported confidence scores, and tooth identification accuracy; \\
		(b) end-to-end system evaluation through case studies examining diagnostic recommendation quality, qualitative evaluation of citation appropriateness, and clinical utility; \\
		% (c) deployment feasibility analysis evaluating infrastructure requirements, operational costs, and suitability for three tier Tanzanian healthcare settings (rural clinics, district hospitals, urban facilities). Evaluation uses publicly available dental radiograph images with synthesized patient histories due to privacy constraints on actual clinical data.
		
		(c) deployment feasibility analysis evaluating infrastructure requirements, operational costs, and suitability for Tanzania's three-tier healthcare infrastructure. Given the substantial variation in resources, connectivity, and technical capacity across different facility types in Tanzania \cite{Edward2024OralHealthTZ}, the thesis proposes and evaluates three distinct deployment configurations tailored to rural clinics, district hospitals, and urban referral facilities. Table~\ref{tab:deployment_scenarios} outlines the proposed configurations, specifying infrastructure assumptions, optimal model combinations, and projected annual operational costs for each tier. The evaluation investigates whether these configurations are technically feasible, clinically adequate, and economically sustainable in their respective contexts. Evaluation uses publicly available dental radiograph images with synthesized patient histories due to privacy constraints on actual clinical data.
		
	\end{itemize}
	
