	\subsection{Limitations of the Study}
	The following limitations are acknowledged and should be considered when interpreting the research findings and assessing the generalizability of conclusions:
	
	\begin{itemize}
		\item \textbf{Imaging Modality Scope:} The study is limited to periapical radiographs, excluding panoramic radiographs, bitewing images, and cone beam computed tomography (CBCT). This decision was necessitated by: \\
		(a) limited availability of publicly accessible, comprehensively labeled datasets for these modalities 
		\cite{huang2024multimodal_dental} \\
		(b) the predominance of periapical imaging in routine Tanzanian dental practice, particularly in resource constrained settings where advanced imaging equipment may be unavailable \cite{Edward2024OralHealthTZ}; \\
		(c) the diagnostic sufficiency of periapical views for the most prevalent conditions targeted in this research. Consequently, system performance and conclusions should not be assumed to generalize to other imaging modalities without empirical validation.
		
		\item \textbf{Dataset Constraints and Synthetic Data:} Evaluation relies on publicly available datasets rather than proprietary clinical data from Tanzanian healthcare facilities. This limitation introduces several considerations: \\
		(a) publicly available datasets may not fully represent the image quality distribution, anatomical variations, or pathology presentations encountered in Tanzanian clinical practice; \\
		(b) patient history data and clinical notes are synthesized for experimental purposes due to privacy and confidentiality restrictions on actual patient records, potentially limiting the realism of multimodal scenarios; \\
		(c) ground truth diagnostic labels are not available for all test cases, precluding traditional classification metrics (precision, recall, F1) for many evaluation scenarios. These constraints may affect the external validity of findings, though the comparative nature of evaluations (across models and configurations) partially mitigates this concern.
		
		\item \textbf{Use of Pre-trained Models Without Fine-Tuning:} The system exclusively employs pre-trained models accessed via API (for cloud providers) or Ollama (for local models), without any domain-specific fine-tuning on dental radiographs. While this design choice aligns with the research objective of developing deployable systems without requiring extensive labeled datasets or computational resources for training, it carries inherent limitations: \\
		(a) specialized fine-tuning on dental-specific datasets could potentially improve diagnostic accuracy, particularly for subtle pathologies or rare conditions that may be underrepresented in general training data; \\
		(b) the system inherits any biases, limitations, or blind spots present in the base models' training distributions; 
		
		\item \textbf{Knowledge Base Coverage and Currency:} The constructed knowledge base represents a curated subset of available dental guidelines rather than comprehensive coverage of all dental specialties, procedures, and conditions. Specific limitations include: \\
		(a) primary reliance on the Tanzanian Standard Treatment Guidelines, which may not address all clinical scenarios encountered in practice; \\
		(b) limited inclusion of peer reviewed literature beyond key systematic reviews and meta-analyses \cite{Dashti2024DLCariesUmbrella,Arzani2025AICariesUmbrella,MADANKUMAR20261}; \\
		(c) static snapshot of guidelines at the time of system development, without mechanisms for automatic updates as policies evolve. System recommendations are therefore bounded by the scope, currency, and quality of source documents \cite{world2024global,Edward2024OralHealthTZ,tanzania_oral_health_policy}.
		
		\item \textbf{Absence of RAG Ablation Studies:} The current evaluation framework compares different vision models within the RAG-enhanced system but does not include systematic ablation studies isolating the specific contribution of retrieval augmentation versus non-RAG baselines. This limitation constrains conclusions about: \\
		(a) the magnitude of hallucination reduction attributable to RAG; \\
		(b) the relative importance of retrieval quality versus generation capability; 
		
		\item \textbf{Clinical Validation Scope:} Evaluation is primarily technical and system-focused rather than clinical, with the following implications: \\
		(a) no large-scale clinical trials involving practicing Tanzanian dentists have been conducted to validate system utility, trustworthiness, or workflow integration; \\
		(b) assessment of diagnostic accuracy relies on proxy measures (model confidence, citation quality) rather than direct comparison to expert consensus or histopathological confirmation; \\
		(c) user experience, adoption barriers, and impact on clinical decision-making remain unexplored. The system is explicitly positioned as a proof-of-concept requiring rigorous clinical validation before any consideration of deployment, consistent with recommendations for responsible AI development in healthcare \cite{ji2023survey,Wada2025RAGRadiology,Rokhshad2025,schwendicke2022ai_global}.
		
		\item \textbf{Generalizability to Tanzanian Context:} While the system is explicitly designed with Tanzanian resource constraints and clinical guidelines in mind, several factors limit generalizability claims: \\
		(a) available datasets may not adequately represent the full spectrum of Tanzanian patient populations, disease presentations, or radiographic equipment variability; \\
		(b) the knowledge base, while including Tanzanian STG, may not capture all regional variations in clinical practice, medication availability, or healthcare delivery models; \\
		(c) deployment feasibility analysis is based on published infrastructure data rather than on-the-ground validation across diverse facility types \cite{Edward2024OralHealthTZ,tanzania_oral_health_policy}. Generalization to other regions or countries would require analogous knowledge base customization and validation.
		
		\item \textbf{Regulatory and Ethical Considerations:} This research explicitly does not pursue medical device regulatory approval (e.g., FDA, Tanzania Medicines and Medical Devices Authority clearance) and should not be interpreted as producing a clinically deployable system. Key limitations include: \\
		(a) absence of formal risk classification, clinical validation protocols, or quality management system integration; \\
		(b) no assessment of medicolegal implications, liability frameworks, or requirements for human oversight in different jurisdictions; \\
		(c) lack of comprehensive bias and fairness evaluation across patient demographic groups; \\
		(d) no consideration of long-term outcomes, adverse event monitoring, or post-deployment surveillance mechanisms \cite{schwendicke2022ai_global,schwendicke2020artificial}. These regulatory, ethical, and safety dimensions are explicitly scoped out and identified as critical future work requirements.
		
		\item \textbf{Economic and Sustainability Analysis:} While cost comparisons across model providers are included, comprehensive economic analysis is beyond current scope: \\
		(a) total cost of ownership calculations for different deployment scenarios (including hardware, maintenance, training, support) are not performed; \\
		(b) sustainability considerations including model update cycles, dependency maintenance, and technical support requirements are not addressed; \\
		(c) analysis of economic impact on healthcare delivery, potential cost savings, or return on investment is not conducted. These dimensions represent important directions for translational research beyond this proof-of-concept phase.
		
	\end{itemize}
	
	
