	\section{Research Contributions}
	This thesis makes the following contributions to the fields of software engineering, knowledge-grounded clinical decision support in dentistry, and multimodal AI systems:
	
	\textbf{1. A Modular RAG-Based Sequential Pipeline Architecture.}
	The thesis specifies a modular three-stage sequential architecture (vision analysis → knowledge retrieval → clinical reasoning) that enables flexible model selection at each stage. Unlike monolithic multimodal models, this design supports mixing local and cloud providers (9 vision models, 5 LLM providers) for cost-optimized deployment. The architecture is designed with clearly defined interfaces, data flows, and orchestration logic implemented via FastAPI framework, providing a reusable reference design for software engineers developing similar medical AI systems. This architectural contribution addresses the challenge of composing specialized AI models into coherent end-to-end pipelines for domain-specific applications.
	
	\textbf{2. An End-to-End Production-Ready System for Clinical Decision Support.}
	The work implements a complete software system covering data ingestion, preprocessing, multimodal feature extraction, semantic retrieval, inference orchestration, and structured response generation. The system includes: \\
	(a) RESTful API design with authentication and role-based access control; \\
	(b) integration of relational databases (PostgreSQL) for patient records with vector stores (Chroma) for guideline retrieval; \\
	(c) practice management functionality to maximise the applicability of the system in a dental clinic setup (appointments, clinical notes, prescriptions); \\
	(d) real-time performance monitoring and evaluation dashboard. Particular emphasis is placed on system-level concerns such as error handling, latency optimization, and cost tracking, demonstrating practical software engineering considerations for deploying AI in clinical settings.
	
	\textbf{3. Knowledge Base Modeling and RAG Integration for Domain Adaptation.}
	The thesis defines a schema and storage strategy for representing international and Tanzania-specific dental guidelines, and integrates this with a retrieval-augmented generation pipeline. This operationalizes RAG for a concrete clinical domain, including document chunking strategies, embedding generation (Nomic-embed-text, mxbai-embed-large), vector indexing (Chroma), context construction, prompt engineering strategies, and grounding mechanisms that reduce hallucination while maintaining domain-specific accuracy. The knowledge base design demonstrates how AI systems can be adapted to regional healthcare contexts through modular knowledge representation, with all recommendations including explicit page citations to source guidelines.
	
	\textbf{4. Comprehensive Multi-Model Evaluation Framework for Resource-Constrained Deployment.}
	Rather than traditional supervised classification metrics requiring ground truth labels, the thesis proposes an evaluation framework that incorporates system level performance indicators for  clinical deployment suitability in a resource constrained clinical practice including: \\
	(a) inference latency and throughput; \\ 
	(b) resource utilization (model size, RAM requirements, CPU usage); \\
	(c) operational costs (per-request and annual projections); \\
	(d) model-intrinsic quality metrics (confidence scores, citation counts, response completeness); \\
	(e) deployment suitability analysis for three-tier healthcare infrastructure. This holistic assessment, implemented through a real time evaluation dashboard, treats the artifact as an integrated software system rather than isolated models, providing evidence-based model selection guidelines for different deployment scenarios (rural/offline, district/hybrid, urban/cloud).
	
	\textbf{5. Multi-Provider Model Selection Framework and Cost Analysis.}
	The system implements a configurable architecture supporting 9 vision models and 5 LLM providers with dynamic model switching via configuration API. A comprehensive cost analysis demonstrates annual operational costs ranging from \$0 (local models: Gemma3, LLaVA) to \$456 (GPT-4o) for 50 cases/day, with deployment recommendations tailored to Tanzania's healthcare context. The evaluation framework provides empirical evidence for cost-performance tradeoffs, enabling evidence-based decisions about model deployment in resource-constrained settings. This contribution addresses the critical gap between general-purpose AI tools and the economic realities of low-resource healthcare systems.
	
	\textbf{6. Implementation Using Open-Source Technologies and Reproducible Methods.}
	The system is implemented using exclusively open-source frameworks (FastAPI, LangChain, Chroma, Ollama) and publicly available datasets, ensuring reproducibility and lowering barriers to entry for future researchers and developers. The complete backend and frontend source code, API documentation, deployment instructions, and evaluation scripts are made available, serving as a practical foundation for extending the work to other medical imaging domains or regional contexts. The modular design and documented architecture facilitate adaptation to different clinical guidelines, languages, or healthcare disciplines or systems.
	
	\textbf{7. Design Insights for AI Deployment in Resource-Constrained Healthcare Settings.}
	Through analysis of system requirements and constraints in Tanzanian clinical settings (1:360,000 dentist-to-population ratio, limited specialist access, intermittent connectivity), the thesis derives evidence-based design implications regarding: \\
	(a) computational efficiency (local models require 4-16GB RAM, cloud models require only 4GB); \\
	(b) offline capability (local models enable fully offline operation); \\
	(c) cost optimization (hybrid deployments reduce costs by 80\% while maintaining clinical quality); \\
	(d) knowledge base localization (region-specific guidelines can be integrated without model retraining). These insights inform software requirements and architectural trade-offs for developing clinically deployable AI tools in low resource environments, with broader applicability to other developing regions facing similar healthcare infrastructure challenges.
