	This chapter surveys the foundational literature across four interconnected domains that inform the design and implementation of the proposed RAG-based multimodal system for dental radiograph analysis. Section \ref{sec:ai_dental} examines artificial intelligence applications in dental radiograph interpretation, tracing the evolution from traditional computer-aided detection using convolutional neural networks to modern vision language models. Section \ref{sec:multimodal} explores multimodal AI architectures in medical diagnostics, with emphasis on strategies for integrating visual and textual clinical data. Section \ref{sec:llms} reviews large language models in clinical contexts, addressing their capabilities, limitations, and the critical challenge of hallucination in safety critical medical applications. Section \ref{sec:rag} provides an in-depth technical analysis of Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) as a paradigm for knowledge grounded reasoning, including retrieval mechanisms, embedding models, and applications in healthcare. The chapter concludes with Section \ref{sec:gap}, synthesizing the reviewed literature to identify specific research gaps that this thesis addresses.
	
