	\section{Artificial Intelligence for Dental Radiograph Analysis}
	\label{sec:ai_dental}
	
	Dental radiography remains the cornerstone of modern dental diagnostics, providing essential visual evidence for identifying pathologies, guiding treatment planning, and monitoring oral health over time \cite{white_pharoah_radiology}. The interpretation of radiographic images, including periapical, bitewing, and panoramic views requires specialized expertise to detect abnormalities such as dental caries, periodontal bone loss, periapical lesions, and root fractures. However, diagnostic accuracy and consistency exhibit significant inter-observer and intra-obser variability, with kappa scores ($\kappa$) often in the moderate range ($\approx$0.4–0.7) for radiographic assessments in dentistry, indicating only partial agreement between clinicians \cite{hintze1998reliability_caries,pillai2022interobserver_demirjian,saunders2001radiographic_reliability}. This variability creates opportunities for artificial intelligence to augment human expertise and improve diagnostic reliability \cite{putra2021ai_dental_radiography}.
	
	\subsection{Deep Learning for Caries Detection: From CNNs to Modern Architectures}
	
	Early AI systems for dental radiographs applied convolutional neural networks (CNNs) to tasks such as caries detection, tooth classification, and pathology recognition \cite{litjens2017survey,schwendicke2021demystifying_ai}. In these pipelines, radiographs are pre-processed (cropping, normalization, augmentation) and passed through a CNN backbone (e.g., VGG, ResNet, EfficientNet), followed by a classification head trained with cross-entropy loss.
	
	Lee et al.~\cite{lee2019deep} employed a ResNet-50 architecture for caries detection on
	periapical radiographs and reported high diagnostic performance, with sensitivity and
	specificity in the 0.8 range, for different teeth numbers (anatomical) and teeth surfaces. The core residual block computes the output vector
	\(\boldsymbol{y}\) as
	
	\begin{equation}
		\boldsymbol{y} = \mathcal{F}\bigl(\boldsymbol{x}; \{W_i\}\bigr) + \boldsymbol{x},
		\label{eq:residual-block}
	\end{equation}
	
	where \(\boldsymbol{x}\) is the block input, \(\mathcal{F}(\cdot)\) is the residual mapping
	implemented by stacked convolutional layers with parameters \(\{W_i\}\), and the skip
	connection \(\boldsymbol{x}\) enables stable training of very deep networks.
	
	Golkarieh et al. \cite{Golkarieh2025DeepDentalPanoramic} evaluated multiple deep learning approaches for classifying dental conditions on panoramic radiographs. Their hybrid CNN-Random Forest model achieved 85.4\% accuracy, outperforming fine-tuned pre-trained architectures including VGG16 (82.3\%), Xception (80.9\%), and ResNet50 (79.5\%) concluding that Hybrid CNN-based approaches combining feature extraction with Random Forest classification provide superior discriminative capability for dental condition detection on manually annotated regions compared to standalone architectures. Cejudo et al. \cite{cejudo2021classification_radiographs} compared three architectures (baseline CNN, ResNet-34, capsule network) for classifying radiograph types, with all models achieving $>$98\% accuracy. Conclusion was made that although higher accuracy, F1-score, precision, and sensitivity of were observed on ResNet than baseline CNN and CapsNet (p $<$ 0.05), regardless of the models, high classification accuracies were achieved. More over Image features considered for classification were consistent with expert reasoning.
	
	Recent systematic and umbrella reviews synthesize the growing body of evidence. Putra et al. \cite{putra2021ai_dental_radiography} reviewed AI applications in dental radiography, categorizing studies by purpose including caries diagnosis, periapical pathology detection, and periodontal bone loss assessment. They noted that while most studies demonstrate strong potential, further development is needed before clinical implementation due to challenges including lack of dataset size justification and unstandardized reporting formats.
	
	Dashti et al. \cite{Dashti2024DLCariesUmbrella} conducted a comprehensive umbrella review of deep learning algorithms for caries detection across 15 systematic reviews. They found that deep learning models achieved a pooled sensitivity of about 0.87, pooled specificity of about 0.89, and a pooled AUROC of roughly 0.93, indicating strong overall discriminative performance for radiographic caries detection.
	
	Arzani et al. \cite{Arzani2025AICariesUmbrella} performed a parallel umbrella review, reporting pooled sensitivity of 0.85 (95\% CI: 0.83 to 0.93) and specificity of 0.90 (95\% CI: 0.85 to 0.95). They concluded that caries diagnosis using AI is accurate and its use in clinical practice is justified, while noting that future studies should focus on specific subpopulations and real world validation.
	
	Negi et al.~\cite{negi2025ai_caries_umbrella} synthesized evidence from several systematic reviews on artificial intelligence for caries diagnosis and detection. They reported that convolutional neural network (CNN) based models generally achieve high diagnostic performance across different radiographic modalities, demonstrating high sensitivity, specificity, and area under the curve in the caries detection, segmentation, and classification tests, appearing promising for clinical support. At the same time, they emphasized that
	ethical considerations, clinical interpretability, and cautious real world deployment remain critical challenges that must be addressed before routine use
	in practice.
	
	\subsection{Limitations of Current Approaches: Binary Classification and Missing Context}
	
	Despite strong performance, most current imaging models share several limitations that constrain their integration into comprehensive clinical decision support \cite{schwendicke2020artificial,inchingolo2025ai_dentistry_review,putra2021ai_dental_radiography}:
	
	\textbf{Task-Specific Classification Paradigm.} Most models operate as binary or multi-class classifiers, outputting probabilities such as $P(\text{caries} \mid \mathbf{x}) \in [0,1]$ without severity grading, treatment recommendations, or differential diagnoses \cite{putra2021ai_dental_radiography}. This narrow focus fails to capture the holistic diagnostic process whereby clinicians integrate multiple findings and consider treatment options \cite{schwendicke2020artificial}.
	
	\textbf{Context-Free Operation.} Models typically process radiographs in isolation, ignoring contextual information such as patient age, medical history, dietary habits, and previous dental treatment. Classical radiology teaching emphasizes that radiographic appearances must be interpreted together with clinical findings and history rather than as stand alone evidence \cite{white_pharoah_radiology}, which current models do not explicitly model. 
	In probabilistic terms, clinical diagnosis requires Bayesian integration
	
	\begin{equation}
		P(\text{caries} | \mathbf{x}, \mathbf{h}) = \frac{P(\mathbf{x} | \text{caries}, \mathbf{h}) \cdot P(\text{caries} | \mathbf{h})}{P(\mathbf{x} | \mathbf{h})}
	\end{equation}
	
	where $\mathbf{x}$ is the radiographic image and $\mathbf{h}$ is patient history. Current models approximate $P(\text{caries} | \mathbf{x}, \mathbf{h}) \approx P(\text{caries} | \mathbf{x})$, discarding prior information $P(\text{caries} | \mathbf{h})$ 
	
	
	\textbf{Black-Box Nature and Limited Explainability.} Deep learning models provide predictions without transparent reasoning \cite{holzinger2017explainableai}. While explainability techniques such as Grad-CAM highlight influential image regions (Figure ~\ref{fig:grad_CAM}), they do not link predictions to diagnostic criteria or guideline statements that clinicians can verify
	
	\textbf{Limited Generalization Across Populations.} Models trained on datasets from high income countries may not generalize to populations with different disease profiles or radiographic equipment quality \cite{schwendicke2022ai_global}.
	
	\textbf{Absence of Guideline Grounding.} Current reviews on safety and ethical aspects of dental AI highlight that most existing systems are not explicitly linked to clinical guidelines or evidence based literature at the interface level, raising concerns about hallucinated recommendations and undermining clinician confidence.
	\cite{Rokhshad2025,schwendicke2022ai_global}. To date, there are few, if any, published dental AI tools that systematically expose guideline passages and citations alongside their recommendations, in contrast to the knowledge-grounded design pursued in this thesis 
	
