	\subsection{Vision-Language Models for Medical Imaging}
	Vision language models (VLMs) represent an evolutionary step in dental AI, moving beyond isolated classification tasks toward multimodal reasoning that combines visual understanding with natural language generation, enabling medical AI systems to generate diagnostic reports, answer image related questions, and integrate visual findings with textual clinical information. \cite{Li2023MultimodalFoundationModels}.
	
	Figure~\ref{fig:dental_ai_evolution} illustrates the progression of dental AI architectures from early CNNs focused on binary detection to modern RAG-enhanced systems that provide knowledge-grounded, explainable recommendations the paradigm pursued in this thesis (design science research). \\
	\\
	
	\begin{figure}[H]
		\centering
		\includegraphics[width=0.95\textwidth]{figures/dental_ai_evolution.png}
		\caption{Evolution of AI architectures for dental radiograph analysis from binary CNN classifiers (2018) to RAG-enhanced vision language models (2025) that ground recommendations in clinical guidelines.}
		\label{fig:dental_ai_evolution}
	\end{figure}
	
	Mine et al.~\cite{mine2025benchmarking_multimodal_llms_dental} evaluated four
	multimodal large language models (ChatGPT-4o, OpenAI o1, Claude 3.5 Sonnet, and
	Gemini 2.0 Flash) on 353 questions from the Japanese National Dental Licensing
	Examination. All models performed substantially better on text-only questions
	(roughly 80--90\% correct) than on visually based questions (roughly 45--70\%),
	indicating that multimodal LLMs are currently much stronger at text understanding
	than at complex dental image interpretation (Figure~\ref{fig:mine_results}). The authors concluded that while
	multimodal LLMs show promising performance on text-based scenarios, significant
	challenges remain for reliable clinical use in image-heavy tasks.
	
	
	\begin{figure}[htbp]
		\centering
		\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{figures/mine_results.png}
		\caption{Performance gap on the Japanese National Dental Licensing Examination: multimodal LLMs achieve 79.9--92.2\% on text questions but only 45.6--67.8\% on visual questions. Data from Mine et al.~\cite{mine2025benchmarking_multimodal_llms_dental}.}
		\label{fig:mine_results}
	\end{figure}
	
	Zhang et al.~\cite{zhang2023biomedclip} introduced BiomedCLIP, a multimodal
	foundation model pretrained on approximately 15 million biomedical image--text
	pairs. Using contrastive learning to align image and text embeddings in a
	medically meaningful space, BiomedCLIP achieved state-of-the-art performance on
	several biomedical classification and retrieval benchmarks ~\cite{zhang2023biomedclip}. Its training
	objective maximizes similarity for matched image--text pairs while minimizing
	similarity for mismatched pairs; in simplified form, a CLIP-style loss can be
	written as
	
	\begin{equation}
		\mathcal{L}
		= -\frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^{N}
		\log \frac{\exp(\mathrm{sim}(\mathbf{i}_i, \mathbf{t}_i)/\tau)}
		{\sum_{j=1}^{N}\exp(\mathrm{sim}(\mathbf{i}_i, \mathbf{t}_j)/\tau)},
	\end{equation}
	
	where $\mathrm{sim}(\mathbf{i}, \mathbf{t})$ denotes cosine similarity between
	normalized image and text embeddings and $\tau$ is a temperature parameter
	controlling the sharpness of the distribution. This training strategy allows
	BiomedCLIP to act as a general-purpose medical vision encoder that can be
	combined with downstream language models.
	
	Building on this line of work, Meng et al.~\cite{meng2025dentvlm} proposed
	DentVLM, a multimodal vision language model specifically engineered for
	comprehensive dental diagnosis. DentVLM was trained on a large scale dataset of
	over 110{,}000 images and more than 2.4 million visual question--answer pairs,
	covering seven 2D oral imaging modalities and 36 diagnostic tasks. In a clinical
	evaluation involving 25 dentists, DentVLM matched or exceeded junior dentists'
	performance on most tasks and reduced diagnostic time by roughly 15--20\%,
	suggesting that carefully designed dental specific VLMs can provide practical
	support in busy clinical workflows.
	
	\subsection{Deterministic Anatomical Validation}
	
	A specific challenge in applying VLMs to dental radiographs is ensuring anatomical and
	tooth numbering consistency. Vision language models can produce anatomically implausible
	outputs, for example, assigning tooth numbers that cannot appear together in a single
	periapical view or mixing maxillary and mandibular quadrants in one image. To mitigate
	this, a separate deterministic validation layer can be inserted between the vision
	subsystem and the rest of the pipeline. This layer enforces rules derived from standard
	numbering systems and imaging geometry, such as quadrant based FDI tooth codes and
	constraints on which teeth can reasonably co-occur in a given projection
	\cite{integrated_tooth_numbering_fdi}. Evidence from automated numbering systems shows
	that explicitly modeling quadrant and position information improves consistency and
	accuracy of tooth identification across radiographic modalities \cite{integrated_tooth_numbering_fdi}.
	
	From a software-architecture perspective, this design follows a common pattern in
	safety critical AI: probabilistic model outputs are wrapped by a simpler, rule based
	monitor that checks them against explicit safety or consistency properties before they
	are used for downstream decisions \cite{safety_monitor_ml_perception,amlas_safety_assurance}. 
	Such monitors are widely recommended for machine learning components in autonomous and
	safety critical systems, where learned perception must be constrained by deterministic
	safety logic.
	
	
