	\section{Multimodal AI in Medical Diagnostics}
	\label{sec:multimodal}
	
	Clinical decision support requires integration of heterogeneous data modalities,
	including pixel level radiographic information, token level patient histories,
	and structured clinical guidelines. Multimodal architectures aim to encode and
	combine these different sources within a single system.
	
	\subsection{Multimodal Foundation Models}
	
	Li et al.~\cite{Li2023MultimodalFoundationModels} survey the taxonomy and
	evolution of multimodal foundation models, from task specific specialists to
	general purpose assistants. They highlight that many recent vision language
	assistants adopt a common three part architecture: a vision encoder that maps
	images to visual embeddings, a projection or alignment module that brings visual
	features into the language model's representation space, and a large language
	model that generates text conditioned on multimodal tokens
	\cite{Li2023MultimodalFoundationModels}. This pattern underpins a broad class of
	multimodal LLM-style systems, even though individual models may differ in
	implementation details.
	
	\subsection{Sequential vs.\ Unified Multimodal Architectures}
	
	Multimodal medical AI systems typically employ one of two high level fusion
	strategies.
	
	\textbf{Unified assistant-style models.} Large, general purpose assistants such
	as GPT-4V and Gemini couple a vision encoder to a language model via a
	projection module, providing a unified interface that can jointly reason over
	visual and textual inputs \cite{Li2023MultimodalFoundationModels}. These systems
	offer strong integration and convenient APIs but have practical limitations:
	their architectures and training data are proprietary, access is usually
	restricted to cloud endpoints requiring reliable internet connectivity, and
	options for domain specific customization and formal regulatory assurance are
	limited.
	
	\textbf{Sequential pipelines (chained tools).} An alternative is to use separate
	models for each modality, with explicitly defined intermediate representations.
	This aligns with the ``chaining multimodal tools with LLMs'' paradigm described
	by Li et al., where vision, retrieval, and reasoning components are orchestrated
	rather than collapsed into a single monolithic model
	\cite{Li2023MultimodalFoundationModels}. The architecture proposed in this
	thesis follows this pattern: imaging, retrieval, and language components are
	decoupled but coordinated, which enables modularity (components can be swapped
	or upgraded), interpretability (intermediate outputs can be inspected), and
	better control over computational and monetary cost in resource constrained
	settings (Figure~\ref{fig:unified_vs_sequential}).\\
	\\
	
	
	\begin{figure}[H]
		\centering
		\includegraphics[width=0.95\textwidth]{figures/unified_vs_sequential.png}
		\caption{Comparison of unified multimodal architectures (GPT-4V, Gemini) versus sequential pipelines.}
		\label{fig:unified_vs_sequential}
	\end{figure}
	
	The proposed system implements a three stage sequential architecture:
	(1) a vision model processes the radiograph and outputs a structured JSON
	representation of tooth level findings;
	(2) a retrieval-augmented generation
	subsystem retrieves relevant passages from a curated guideline and textbook
	corpus; and
	(3) a language model synthesizes visual findings, retrieved...
	passages, and patient clinical history into clinical recommendations with explicit
	citations. This design exemplifies the chained tool paradigm for multimodal
	assistants described in recent surveys \cite{Li2023MultimodalFoundationModels}.
	
	\subsection{Multimodal Dental Datasets}
	
	Progress in multimodal dental AI is constrained by the limited number of
	publicly available datasets that combine dental images with rich clinical text
	or structured records \cite{Huang2024MultimodalDentalDataset,Wang2025MMDentalDataset}.
	Huang et al.~\cite{Huang2024MultimodalDentalDataset} introduced a dataset
	comprising 169 patients with three dental imaging modalities (CBCT, panoramic,
	and periapical radiographs). The dataset includes 329 CBCT scans, with a subset
	of CBCT images paired with periapical radiographs, and panoramic radiographs
	paired with both CBCT and periapical images. The authors explicitly note the
	shortage of publicly available dental datasets and motivate their multimodal
	resource as a way to facilitate machine learning research and clinical services
	in dentistry. Although the dataset is multimodal in terms of imaging, the number
	of high quality periapical images remains limited compared to CBCT scans, which
	constrains periapical specific modeling.
	
	Wang et al.~\cite{Wang2025MMDentalDataset} presented MMDental, a larger
	multimodal dataset of 660 patients that includes 3D CBCT images with detailed
	expert medical records, covering initial diagnoses and follow-up documentation.
	They emphasize that most prior public dental datasets are predominantly
	imaging only (2D radiographs or CBCT) without comprehensive medical records or
	longitudinal follow up; MMDental is positioned as the first large dataset to
	pair tooth level CBCT data with rich expert documentation
	\cite{Wang2025MMDentalDataset}. Taken together, these works show that existing
	public datasets are still largely concentrated in a small number of centers,
	with limited geographic diversity and relatively scarce periapical data, which
	limits the generalizability and scope of multimodal dental AI systems
	\cite{Huang2024MultimodalDentalDataset,Wang2025MMDentalDataset}.
	
	\subsection{Model Selection and Provider Frameworks}
	
	Real world deployment requires balancing multiple, often conflicting objectives,
	including diagnostic accuracy, inference latency, hardware requirements, cost,
	and reliability. The architecture in this thesis explicitly supports a
	multi provider framework in which different vision models and language models
	can be evaluated and combined. This enables policy based selection of model
	configurations tailored to the available clinical infrastructure (for example,
	preferring local models in offline settings or routing selected cases to cloud
	models when bandwidth and budget permit), while keeping the overall pipeline and
	interfaces fixed. Such a design is particularly important in low and
	middle income settings, where infrastructure constraints and cost considerations
	play a central role in determining which AI components can be deployed in
	practice.
	
