	\section{Large Language Models in Clinical Contexts}
	\label{sec:llms}
	
	Large language models (LLMs) based on transformer architectures have been
	explored extensively in healthcare for clinical documentation, question
	answering, triage support, and decision support applications
	\cite{thirunavukarasu2023large}. Reviews highlight that such models encode a
	substantial amount of biomedical knowledge and can perform competitively on
	medical examination style benchmarks, while also stressing important risks
	related to safety, bias, and transparency \cite{thirunavukarasu2023large}.
	
	\subsection{LLM Capabilities and Orchestration}
	
	LLMs implement self attention over token sequences and are trained to predict
	the next token given preceding context \cite{thirunavukarasu2023large}. The
	multi head self attention mechanism in a typical transformer block computes
	
	\begin{equation}
		\mathrm{Attention}(Q, K, V)
		= \mathrm{softmax}\!\left(\frac{QK^\top}{\sqrt{d_k}}\right)V,
	\end{equation}
	
	where $Q$, $K$, and $V$ denote query, key, and value matrices, and the scaling
	by $\sqrt{d_k}$ stabilizes the softmax operation for high-dimensional keys.
	
	Bhayana  
	\cite{chatbots_Rajesh_2024} reviews practical applications of
	chatbots and large language models in radiology, outlining clinical and research
	use cases including conversational assistance, report generation, and protocol
	selection. Findings from radiology show that coupling LLMs with retrieval and
	multi step reasoning tools (e.g., RAG, iterative retrieval pipelines) can
	substantially improve answer quality and safety compared to querying models in
	isolation \cite{Wada2025RAGRadiology,Wind2025RaRRadiology}. These studies
	demonstrate that structured orchestration, combining retrieval, reasoning, and
	external knowledge sources, markedly outperforms naive single step prompting on
	radiology consultation and question answering tasks.
	
	\subsection{Hallucination and Safety in Medical LLMs}
	
	A major concern in medical use of LLMs is hallucination: the generation of
	fluent but factually incorrect or unsupported content. Ji et al.\cite{ji2023survey} provide a
	comprehensive survey and taxonomy of hallucination in natural language
	generation, distinguishing between factual hallucinations (contradicting
	established knowledge), input conflicting hallucinations (inconsistent with
	provided context), and other forms of unfaithful output \cite{ji2023survey}. In
	clinical settings, such errors can translate into unsafe recommendations if not
	properly constrained.
	
	Wada et al.~\cite{Wada2025RAGRadiology} quantified hallucination related safety risks in radiology contrast media consultation by comparing different LLM configurations. A general purpose LLM used without retrieval augmentation produced a substantial proportion of unsafe responses, while combining the same model with retrieval augmented generation (RAG) over institutional protocols markedly reduced the rate of unsafe answers. Specifically, qualitative assessment by a radiologist revealed that hallucinations particularly in contrast dosing and contraindication recommendations were present in 8\% of responses from the base Llama model and were eliminated (to 0\%) in the RAG-enhanced version ($\chi^2_{\text{Yates}} = 6.38$, $p = 0.012$; Fisher $p = 0.0068$). Among 100 test cases, 54\% showed marked improvement with RAG, most notably in safety critical content such as contraindication management and precise dosing guidance, while an additional 33\% demonstrated minor gains. Clinical accuracy scores improved from a mean of 14.2 to 21.5 points (out of 25), and safety considerations improved from 11.8 to 18.7 points (out of 20), demonstrating that RAG substantially enhanced both factual correctness and clinical safety. Wind et al.~\cite{Wind2025RaRRadiology} similarly showed that multi step retrieval and reasoning improved answer quality and robustness on radiology question answering benchmarks compared with single step baselines.
	
	Retrieval based grounding in guideline passages, as demonstrated by Wada et al.,
	represents one of the most effective technical strategies for reducing medical
	hallucinations \cite{Wada2025RAGRadiology,ji2023survey}. Building on this and
	general LLM safety patterns, additional mitigation approaches include schema constrained
	outputs (e.g., requiring structured JSON that can be validated, which this DSR also adopts), tool calling
	patterns (requiring external database queries for specific facts), and
	post generation verification against knowledge bases
	\cite{ji2023survey,schwendicke2022ai_global}. These strategies are particularly relevant in dentistry, where over trust in AI systems and lack of transparency have been identified as key ethical and societal concerns~\cite{schwendicke2022ai_global,Rokhshad2025}. This is especially critical in resource constrained settings where users may over rely on AI recommendations due to limited access to specialist consultation.
	
	Wada et al.\ further explored systematic optimization of local LLMs for Japanese
	medical text processing and protected health information (PHI) extraction,
	demonstrating that careful model selection, prompt design, and fine tuning can
	narrow the performance gap between local and large proprietary models while
	preserving the privacy and deployment advantages of on premise systems
	\cite{Wada2026LocalLLMOptimization}. This supports the broader design choice in
	this thesis to treat LLMs as configurable components within a tool using,
	retrieval augmented architecture, rather than relying on a single fixed model.
	
	
