	\section{Retrieval-Augmented Generation for Knowledge-Grounded Reasoning}
	\label{sec:rag}
	
	Retrieval Augmented Generation (RAG) addresses key limitations of parametric
	language models knowledge cutoffs, hallucination, and the inability to update
	knowledge without retraining by augmenting generation with explicit retrieval
	from external knowledge bases \cite{lewis2020retrieval}.
	
	\subsection{RAG Architecture and Retrieval Mechanisms}
	
	The canonical RAG architecture introduced by Lewis et al.\ combines a neural
	retriever with a neural generator for knowledge intensive NLP tasks
	\cite{lewis2020retrieval}:
	
	\begin{equation}
		p(y \mid q)
		= \sum_{z \in \text{top-}k(q)} p_\eta(z \mid q) \cdot p_\theta(y \mid q, z),
	\end{equation}
	
	where $\eta$ are retriever parameters and $\theta$ are generator parameters.
	Modern RAG implementations typically extend this formulation with document
	ingestion and chunking, embedding based vector indexing, and in some cases
	hybrid dense sparse retrieval and reranking, reflecting contemporary practice in
	knowledge intensive applications \cite{lewis2020retrieval,firoozi2025rag_dentistry,xu2025mega_rag}. Figure~\ref{fig:rag_flowchart} illustrates the complete RAG pipeline architecture implemented in this thesis.
	
	
	\begin{figure}[H]
		\centering
		\includegraphics[width=0.95\textwidth]{figures/rag_flowchart.png}
		\caption{Three-stage RAG pipeline: (1) document ingestion with chunking and embedding, (2) hybrid retrieval combining BM25 and dense search, (3) LLM generation conditioned on retrieved guideline passages with explicit citations.}
		\label{fig:rag_flowchart}
	\end{figure}
	
	Firoozi et al.~\cite{firoozi2025rag_dentistry} provide a mini review of RAG in
	dentistry, outlining core architectural components and the potential for
	developing reliable, evidence aligned AI assistants. They argue that by
	integrating external dental knowledge sources with LLM generative capabilities,
	RAG can mitigate limitations of standalone LLMs, including outdated parametric
	knowledge, limited domain specificity, and hallucination risk.
	
	
	Recent work proposes more advanced RAG variants for medical and public health
	applications. Xu et al.\ \cite{xu2025mega_rag} introduce MEGA-RAG, which
	combines multi source evidence retrieval (dense embeddings, keyword based
	retrieval, and biomedical knowledge graphs) with cross encoder reranking and
	discrepancy aware refinement, reporting substantially reduced hallucination
	rates compared with standard RAG baselines. Wind et al.\
	\cite{Wind2025RaRRadiology} show that multi step retrieval and reasoning
	pipelines improve radiology question answering compared with single step
	retrieval, highlighting the value of iterative retrieval reasoning schemes in
	clinical domains.
	
	\subsection{Evidence for RAG in Clinical Decision Support}
	
	Wada et al.\ \cite{Wada2025RAGRadiology} report a large scale evaluation of RAG
	for clinical decision support in radiology contrast media consultation across 100 simulated clinical scenarios. They demonstrate that augmenting LLMs with retrieval over
	institutional contrast media protocols substantially reduces unsafe responses
	compared to ungrounded use and achieves high citation accuracy, enabling
	clinicians to verify the underlying sources. Their results further show that
	local LLMs combined with RAG can reach performance levels competitive with
	proprietary cloud models, supporting the feasibility of RAG based decision
	support in resource constrained environments.
	
	These findings from radiology consultation suggest that a similar pattern can be
	effective for dental decision support, particularly where national or local
	guidelines specify context specific diagnostic and clinical management protocols.
	
	\subsection{Local Guideline Integration and Low Resource Deployment}
	
	In Tanzania and similar settings, national oral health strategies and Standard
	Treatment Guideline (STG) documents define diagnostic and treatment pathways
	adapted to local disease patterns, drug availability, and infrastructure
	constraints \cite{Edward2024OralHealthTZ,tanzania_oral_health_policy}. Large
	general purpose language models trained on global web scale data are unlikely to
	reliably internalize these locally specific rules.
	
	RAG provides a practical mechanism to encode such local practices: STG and
	policy documents are ingested, segmented, and embedded into a local vector
	store; retrieval queries are composed from structured case data; and the LLM is
	prompted with retrieved passages alongside patient information. Because the
	knowledge base resides locally, this architecture supports on-premise
	deployment with intermittent or no internet connectivity, which is critical for
	rural and under resourced facilities \cite{Edward2024OralHealthTZ}. Updating the
	system for new STG editions or local adaptations requires only re indexing the
	documents, not retraining the underlying models.
	
	Feng et al.~\cite{feng2025hyper_rag} introduced Hyper-RAG, a hypergraph driven retrieval augmented generation approach that captures both pairwise and higher order correlations among domain specific knowledge units to mitigate hallucinations in LLM outputs. Experiments on medical datasets demonstrated that Hyper RAG improved accuracy by an average of 12.3\% over direct LLM use and outperformed Graph RAG and Light RAG by 6.3\% and 6.0\% respectively. Notably, Hyper RAG maintained stable performance with increasing query complexity, while existing methods showed performance degradation. Further validation across nine diverse datasets showed a 35.5\% performance improvement over Light RAG, confirming Hyper RAG's effectiveness in enhancing LLM reliability for high stakes medical applications. These results suggest that more expressive retrieval structures can further enhance knowledge grounded reasoning in clinical contexts.
	
