	\section{Synthesis and Identified Research Gap}
	\label{sec:gap}
	
	The surveyed literature demonstrates substantial progress across multiple
	domains while revealing critical gaps that motivate this research.
	
	\subsection{Summary of Current State}
	
	\textbf{Deep learning for dental imaging.}
	Umbrella and systematic reviews consistently report high diagnostic performance
	for deep learning based caries detection on research datasets, with pooled
	sensitivities, specificities, and AUROC values typically in the high 0.8 to
	low 0.9 range \cite{Dashti2024DLCariesUmbrella,Arzani2025AICariesUmbrella}.
	These results support the viability of CNN based models for image level
	classification of caries and related conditions, confirming their diagnostic viability, but most systems are designed
	as task specific classifiers that operate on radiographs in isolation and do
	not integrate patient history, treatment options, or guideline based reasoning
	\cite{putra2021ai_dental_radiography,inchingolo2025ai_dentistry_review}.
	
	\textbf{Vision--language models.}
	General purpose vision language models and multimodal LLMs show strong
	performance on text based medical question answering and examination style
	benchmarks, yet their performance drops substantially on image heavy or visually
	complex dental tasks \cite{mine2025benchmarking_multimodal_llms_dental}. Domain adapted
	models such as BiomedCLIP \cite{zhang2023biomedclip} and DentVLM \cite{meng2025dentvlm}
	improve medical and dental image understanding by aligning image and text
	embeddings on large domain specific datasets, but they are not explicitly
	designed for guideline grounded, citation based decision support, hence prone to hallucination.
	
	\textbf{Large language models.}
	Large language models achieve strong performance on a wide range of medical
	question answering and clinical documentation tasks
	\cite{thirunavukarasu2023large}, but ungrounded use in clinical scenarios is
	associated with non trivial rates of unsafe or incorrect responses. In radiology
	contrast media consultation, for example, Wada et al.\cite{Wada2025RAGRadiology} report that general LLMs
	used without retrieval augmentation produced a substantial proportion of unsafe
	answers, underscoring the need for explicit grounding and safety mechanisms
	\cite{Wada2025RAGRadiology}.
	
	\textbf{Retrieval-augmented generation.}
	RAG has demonstrated effectiveness in radiology and public health applications
	by combining retrieval over trusted knowledge sources with LLM generation to
	reduce hallucination rates, enable knowledge updates without retraining, and
	support citation based verification of answers
	\cite{lewis2020retrieval,Wada2025RAGRadiology,xu2025mega_rag}. Wada et al.\
	show that retrieval over institutional protocols markedly reduces unsafe
	responses and enables high citation accuracy in radiology consultation, while
	Firoozi et al.\ highlight the potential of RAG to create evidence aligned
	assistants in dentistry \cite{Wada2025RAGRadiology,firoozi2025rag_dentistry}.
	
	\subsection{Critical Gaps Addressed by This Thesis}
	
	\textbf{Gap 1: Knowledge grounded dental AI.}
	To date, there are no widely reported dental AI systems for radiographs that
	explicitly ground their recommendations in clinical guidelines with verifiable
	citations \cite{putra2021ai_dental_radiography,inchingolo2025ai_dentistry_review}.
	This thesis addresses this gap by designing a RAG pipeline that retrieves and
	cites relevant passages from Tanzanian Standard Treatment Guidelines (STGs) and
	related oral health documents for each recommendation (AI clinical assistance).
	
	\textbf{Gap 2: Multimodal integration for periapical radiographs.}
	Most published systems process dental images independently of patient history
	and contextual information, even though clinical decision making relies on
	combining radiographic findings with symptoms, risk factors, and prior
	treatment (clinical history) \cite{putra2021ai_dental_radiography,inchingolo2025ai_dentistry_review}.
	This thesis proposes a sequential architecture that fuses structured outputs
	from periapical radiograph analysis, patient's clinical history, and retrieved guideline
	passages to support context aware decision making.
	
	\textbf{Gap 3: Deployment in resource constrained settings.}
	The majority of dental AI research assumes high resource environments with
	reliable connectivity and dedicated IT infrastructure, whereas countries such
	as Tanzania face persistent challenges including limited internet access and
	very constrained health IT budgets \cite{Edward2024OralHealthTZ,tanzania_oral_health_policy}.
	This thesis implements a multi provider architecture that accommodates both local and cloud based models and allows flexible, cost  and resource efficient model selection, tailored
	to low resource clinical environments.
	
	\textbf{Gap 4: Regional guideline adaptation.}
	Models trained on datasets and guidelines from high income countries cannot
	directly incorporate local protocols or national STGs without additional
	mechanisms. Existing work does not provide modular approaches for adapting
	dental AI systems to country specific guidelines without retraining
	\cite{inchingolo2025ai_dentistry_review,firoozi2025rag_dentistry}. This thesis
	introduces a modular knowledge base and retrieval layer that can be populated
	with country specific guidelines (e.g., Tanzanian STGs) and updated as policies
	change, without modifying the underlying models.
	
	\textbf{Gap 5: Reproducible open-source framework.}
	Many commercial dental AI solutions are proprietary, and research prototypes
	often lack end-to-end, production ready code or detailed deployment guidance
	\cite{inchingolo2025ai_dentistry_review,putra2021ai_dental_radiography}. This
	thesis provides a complete open source codebase, including documented APIs and
	configuration for multiple model providers, to support reproducibility and
	practical adoption.
	
	
	
	
	
	Table~\ref{tab:research_gap} synthesizes these five critical gaps, positioning this thesis at the intersection of knowledge-grounded reasoning, multimodal integration, and deployment feasibility for resource-constrained healthcare systems.
	
