	\subsection{Research Positioning}
	Within this landscape, this thesis positions itself at the intersection of
	dental imaging, multimodal reasoning, and deployment in low resource settings.
	To the best of the author's knowledge, it represents one of the first concrete
	implementations of a retrieval augmented generation pipeline for dental
	radiograph interpretation that explicitly links periapical findings to national
	clinical guidelines via verifiable citations. Building on evidence that RAG
	improves safety and verifiability in radiology consultation \cite{Wada2025RAGRadiology}
	and that deep learning models already achieve high diagnostic accuracy on dental
	radiographs \cite{Dashti2024DLCariesUmbrella,Arzani2025AICariesUmbrella}, this
	work:
	
	\begin{itemize}
		\item designs and qualitatively evaluates a RAG based approach to ground dental
		AI outputs in guideline retrieval (analogous to Wada et al.'s radiology
		findings);
		\item develops a sequential multimodal architecture (vision $\rightarrow$
		retrieval $\rightarrow$ LLM) that enables flexible model selection and
		deterministic validation suitable for resource-constrained deployments; and
		\item provides an open source, modular codebase that analyzing cost performance
		trade offs and aims to deliver practically usable performance while
		offering greater transparency, adaptability, and regional customization.
	\end{itemize}
	
	Collectively, these contributions address critical gaps in current dental AI by
	linking high performing imaging models to guideline grounded reasoning and by
	explicitly targeting the constraints and needs of low resource clinical
	environments.
	
