	% ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
	\section{Research and Design Approach}
	\label{sec:dsr}
	% ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
	
	This research follows the Design Science Research (DSR) methodology (Hevner et al. \cite{Hevner2004}), which frames knowledge
	production around the creation and evaluation of innovative artefacts that solve real world
	problems. DSR is appropriate  in this context because the central challenge, limited access to specialist dental care in Tanzania, inconsistency in radiographic interpretation, and the lack of domain-informed dental AI is more effectively tackled by building and evaluating functional system rather than through theoretical modelling alone. The artefact is a proof-of-concept system; its contribution extends beyond the implemented solution to include the architectural patterns, design principles, and evaluation findings it encapsulates, which can be adapted to other clinical settings and geographic regions.
	
	The DSR framework structures this thesis around three interconnected cycles:
	
	\begin{enumerate}
		
		\item \textbf{Relevance Cycle.} The problem context established in Chapters~1--2 defines
		the design requirements and kernel theory for the artefact. Tanzania's dentist-to-population
		ratio of approximately 1:360{,}000~\cite{Edward2024OralHealthTZ}, significant
		inter-observer and intra-observer variability in radiographic
		interpretation~\cite{hintze1998reliability_caries, pillai2022interobserver_demirjian,
			saunders2001radiographic_reliability}, and the limited explainability of existing dental
		AI systems~\cite{schwendicke2022ai_global, putra2021ai_dental_radiography,
			holzinger2017explainableai} collectively establish the motivation for a modular,
		knowledge-grounded architecture. The outputs of this cycle research objectives O1--O6
		and research questions RQ1--RQ5, inform every architectural decision in this chapter.
		
		\item \textbf{Design Cycle.} This chapter presents the architectural design: a modular,
		RAG-enhanced multimodal system. Design decisions are grounded in established software
		engineering principles; separation of concerns, provider agnostic abstraction,
		defence-in-depth through deterministic validation and in the clinical requirements
		derived from the Relevance Cycle.
		
		\item \textbf{Rigor Cycle.} The design draws on foundational literature reviewed in
		Chapter~2: vision-language model
		architectures~\cite{Li2023MultimodalFoundationModels, zhang2023biomedclip},
		retrieval-augmented generation~\cite{lewis2020retrieval, firoozi2025rag_dentistry},
		hallucination mitigation in clinical
		LLMs~\cite{ji2023survey, Wada2025RAGRadiology}, and deployment considerations for AI
		in resource constrained
		healthcare~\cite{Edward2024OralHealthTZ, tanzania_oral_health_policy}.
		Evaluation
		methods in Chapter~4 are informed by prior work on model selection frameworks for
		healthcare AI~\cite{schwendicke2022ai_global, schwendicke2021demystifying_ai}.
		
	\end{enumerate}
	
	% ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
	\section{Overall System Architecture}
	\label{sec:architecture}
	% ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
	
	The system implements a three-stage sequential pipeline architecture, illustrated in
	Figure~\ref{fig:pipeline}. A periapical radiograph and patient context enter the
	\textit{Vision Analysis} stage, whose structured findings drive \textit{Knowledge Retrieval},
	whose retrieved guideline passages combine with all prior context are taken into the
	\textit{Clinical Reasoning} stage to produce a cited recommendation. An orchestration
	layer implemented in \texttt{CDSSFusionEngine} coordinates the workflow, manages data
	flow between stages, and enforces deterministic clinical validation on all AI-generated
	outputs. The system uses a dual-store persistence strategy: PostgreSQL for structured
	clinical records (patients, encounters, notes, prescriptions, appointments) and ChromaDB
	for semantic retrieval from guideline documents.
	
	\begin{figure}[H]
		\centering
		\includegraphics[width=0.90\textwidth]{figures/fig_pipeline.png}
		\caption{Three-stage sequential pipeline architecture. The orchestration layer coordinates
			all stages; dual data stores support structured patient records (PostgreSQL) and
			semantic guideline retrieval (ChromaDB); the deterministic validation layer enforces
			clinical constraints on all AI outputs before the response is returned to the client.}
		\label{fig:pipeline}
	\end{figure}
	
	\subsection*{Rationale: Sequential Pipeline vs.\ Unified Multimodal Architecture}
	
	The sequential design was deliberately chosen over unified multimodal architectures such as
	GPT-4V or Gemini used end-to-end. Most critically, the sequential approach supports fully
	offline operation using local models, a non-negotiable requirement for rural Tanzanian
	clinics and allows the knowledge base to be updated with new guidelines without retraining
	any model. This aligns with the ``chaining multimodal tools with LLMs'' paradigm described
	by Li et al.~\cite{Li2023MultimodalFoundationModels}, where specialised components are
	orchestrated rather than collapsed into a single model.
	Table~\ref{tab:pipeline_comparison} summarises the key trade-offs.
	
	
	\begin{table}[H]
		\centering
		\caption{Sequential pipeline versus unified multimodal architecture.}
		\label{tab:pipeline_comparison}
		\begin{tabular}{lll}
			\toprule
			\textbf{Criterion} & \textbf{Unified Model} & \textbf{Sequential Pipeline (this work)} \\
			\midrule
			Modularity            & Fixed, monolithic         & High; components independently swappable \\
			Cost control          & Fixed per-request (cloud) & Flexible; local free, cloud only when needed \\
			Interpretability      & Low (end-to-end black box)& High; intermediate outputs inspectable \\
			Offline deployment    & Not possible              & Fully supported via local models \\
			Provider flexibility  & Single provider           & 10 vision models + 5 LLM providers \\
			Knowledge updates     & Requires retraining       & Add documents to knowledge base only \\
			\bottomrule
		\end{tabular}
	\end{table}
	
	
	
