	\paragraph{Multi-Provider Abstraction.}
	The \texttt{VisionClient} class maintains a registry of provider clients and dynamically
	loads the appropriate implementation based on the \texttt{VISION\_MODEL\_PROVIDER}
	configuration value (set in the \texttt{config/visionconfig.py} file or set at runtime by the \texttt{POST '/api/vision/config'} endpoint). Each provider client implements a consistent interface:
	\texttt{analyze\_image(image,~prompt)}, \texttt{analyze\_clinical\_image(image)} for
	dental-specific prompting, and \texttt{get\_model\_info()} for health-check and metadata.
	Provider client instances are maintained as lazy loaded module level singletons, minimising
	startup overhead. This pattern means that adding a new vision provider requires implementing
	only one class without modifying the orchestration engine.
	
	\paragraph{Image Preprocessing.}
	All radiographs undergo standardised preprocessing via \\ \texttt{ImageProcessor} regardless
	of the underlying model. The pipeline performs: (i)~format validation (JPEG, PNG, WebP);
	(ii)~colour-space normalisation to RGB, since DICOM-derived images may be greyscale or
	RGBA; (iii)~aspect preserving resize to a maximum of 1{,}024\,px; and (iv)~optional
	contrast enhancement via PIL \texttt{ImageEnhance} (disabled by default), which is
	particularly relevant for under exposed periapical films common in resource constrained
	settings. All parameters are controlled through \texttt{vision\_settings} and can be
	adjusted at runtime (\texttt{POST '/api/vision/config'}). Figure~\ref{fig:preprocessing_code} shows the core function.
	
	\begin{figure}[H]
		\centering
		\includegraphics[width=0.78\textwidth]{figures/fig_preprocessing_code.png}
		\caption{Core preprocessing function in \texttt{image\_processor.py}. The function
			validates the image format, normalises colour space to RGB, and resizes to a maximum
			of 1{,}024\,px while preserving the original aspect ratio.}
		\label{fig:preprocessing_code}
	\end{figure}
	
	\paragraph{Structured Output Schema.}
	To decouple downstream stages from provider-specific output formats, all vision models are
	prompted to return findings as structured JSON conforming to a predefined schema. The schema
	captures: teeth visible in the field of view; per-finding pathology fields (caries,
	periapical pathology, bone loss, root canal treatment, restorations, other abnormalities),
	each with a presence flag, location, severity, and notes; a natural language primary
	finding; severity and urgency indicators; and two numerical confidence metrics
	(\texttt{image\_quality\_score} and \texttt{diagnostic\_confidence}). Schema compliance is
	achieved through explicit JSON formatting instructions, few-shot examples for smaller local
	models, and a robust fallback parser (\texttt{\_parse\_structured\_response}) that handles
	markdown code fences, surrounding explanatory text, and minor schema deviations. \\ Figure~\ref{fig:json_schema} shows a representative output from the
	\texttt{POST /api/vision/analyze\_image} endpoint with a radiograph image attached along the form data shown in figure ~\ref{fig:form_data}.
	
	\begin{figure}[H]
		\centering
		\includegraphics[width=0.75\textwidth]{figures/form_data.png}
		\caption{Form data submitted to \texttt{POST /api/vision/analyze\_image}}
		\label{fig:form_data}
	\end{figure}
	
	
	\begin{figure}[H]
		\centering
		\includegraphics[width=0.99\textwidth]{figures/fig_json_schema.png}
		\caption{Representative structured JSON output from the vision analysis layer for a
			periapical radiograph showing mesial caries and periapical radiolucency on tooth~47.
			All downstream stages consume this schema regardless of which vision provider produced
			it.}
		\label{fig:json_schema}
	\end{figure}
	
	
	\paragraph{Confidence Scoring.}
	Each provider reports \texttt{image\_quality\_score} (0--1), reflecting technical
	radiograph quality (sharpness, contrast, positioning), and \texttt{diagnostic\_confidence}
	(0--1), reflecting the model's self-assessed certainty about its interpretation. These are
	combined by the orchestration layer into an overall confidence level (Table~\ref{tab:confidence}): high ($\geq 0.80$),
	medium ($0.50$--$0.79$), or low ($< 0.50$). Low confidence can trigger automatic fallback
	to a higher capability cloud model in hybrid deployments.
	
	% ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
	\subsection{Knowledge Base Construction and RAG Pipeline}
	\label{sec:rag}
	% ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
	
	The knowledge base transforms unstructured clinical guideline documents into a semantically
	indexed, retrievable corpus using LangChain and ChromaDB. The design follows the
	retrieve-then-generate RAG paradigm~\cite{lewis2020retrieval}, grounding every generated
	recommendation in explicitly retrieved and traceable source material.
	
	\paragraph{Document Sources.}
	Three source types are ingested, reflecting the dual requirement for regional relevance and
	international best practice:
	\begin{itemize}
		\item \textbf{Tanzania Standard Treatment Guidelines (STG)}: a 618-page Ministry of
		Health document covering health protocols, drug formulary, and clinical
		decision pathways~\cite{tanzania_oral_health_policy}. This is the primary regional
		reference.
		\item \textbf{WHO Oral Health Guidelines}~\cite{who_oral_health}: international standards
		used particularly where the Tanzania STG does not address a specific condition.
		
	\end{itemize}
	
	\paragraph{Ingestion Pipeline.}
	Documents are processed in four steps:
	\begin{enumerate}
		\item \textbf{PDF loading.} \texttt{PyPDFLoader} extracts text with page number metadata
		preserved on every segment.
		\item \textbf{Chunking.} \texttt{RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter} divides text into
		overlapping chunks. The default uses 1{,}500-character chunks with 100 character
		overlap, balancing retrieval precision against contextual richness; both parameters are
		runtime-configurable via the RAG configuration API \texttt{POST /api/rag/config}.
		\item \textbf{Embedding.} Chunks are embedded with the configured model
		(\texttt{nomic-embed-text} via Ollama by default; alternatives: \texttt{mxbai-embed-large}
		and biomedical-specific \texttt{MedEmbed} via HuggingFace).
		\item \textbf{Indexing.} Embeddings and metadata; source document name, page number(s),
		chunk index are stored in ChromaDB, preserving the information required for page level
		citations.
	\end{enumerate}
	
	\paragraph{Retrieval Configuration.}
	The \texttt{RetrieverFactory} supports three runtime-configurable strategies
	(Table~\ref{tab:retrieval_config}). The default MMR strategy balances relevance and
	diversity according to Equation~\eqref{eq:mmr}, which is particularly valuable when the
	knowledge base contains near-duplicate guideline passages across sections of the Tanzania
	STG.
	
	\begin{equation}
		\text{MMR} = \arg\max_{d_i \in \mathcal{D}\setminus\mathcal{S}}
		\Bigl[\lambda \cdot \operatorname{sim}(q,d_i)
		- (1-\lambda) \cdot \max_{d_j \in \mathcal{S}} \operatorname{sim}(d_i,d_j)\Bigr]
		\label{eq:mmr}
	\end{equation}
	
	\noindent where $q$ is the retrieval query, $\mathcal{D}$ is the candidate chunk set,
	$\mathcal{S}$ is the already-selected set, and $\lambda$ controls the relevance--diversity
	trade-off ($\lambda = 1.0$ reduces to pure cosine similarity).
	
	\begin{table}[H]
		\centering
		\caption{RAG retrieval configuration parameters in \texttt{RetrieverFactory}.}
		\label{tab:retrieval_config}
		\begin{tabular}{llll}
			\toprule
			\textbf{Parameter} & \textbf{Default} & \textbf{Range} & \textbf{Description} \\
			\midrule
			\texttt{RETRIEVER\_TYPE}      & \texttt{mmr}  & similarity/mmr/score\_threshold & Retrieval strategy \\
			\texttt{RETRIEVAL\_K}         & 8             & 1--20           & Chunks returned \\
			\texttt{FETCH\_K}             & 20            & ---             & MMR candidate pool \\
			\texttt{LAMBDA\_MULT}         & 1.0           & 0.0--1.0        & Relevance vs.\ diversity \\
			\texttt{SIMILARITY\_THRESHOLD}& 0.6           & 0.0--1.0        & Score-threshold cutoff \\
			\texttt{CHUNK\_SIZE}          & 1500          & 500--2500       & Characters per chunk \\
			\texttt{CHUNK\_OVERLAP}       & 100           & 0--500          & Overlap between chunks \\
			\bottomrule
		\end{tabular}
	\end{table}
	
	
	At inference time the fusion engine constructs a pathology specific retrieval query from
	the structured vision findings using identified pathology codes and the focus tooth number
	rather than raw summary text to prevent model artefacts from contaminating the retrieval
	process. Retrieved chunks, together with their source page numbers, are assembled verbatim
	into the reasoning prompt, ensuring every recommendation is anchored to verifiable source
	material.
	
	% ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
	\subsection{Clinical Reasoning Module}
	\label{sec:reasoning}
	% ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
	
	The clinical reasoning module synthesises patient history, structured vision findings, and
	retrieved guideline passages into a structured, cited recommendation. It abstracts five LLM
	providers (Table~\ref{tab:llm_providers}) through a unified interface, enabling the same
	reasoning logic to execute fully offline or against cloud APIs. This directly addresses the
	hallucination problem identified in the
	literature~\cite{ji2023survey, Wada2025RAGRadiology} by conditioning every generation step
	on explicitly retrieved, traceable evidence.
	
	\begin{table}[H]
		\centering
		\caption{Supported LLM providers for the clinical reasoning module.}
		\label{tab:llm_providers}
		{\small
			\begin{tabular}{p{2.0cm}p{4.0cm}p{1.8cm}p{3.8cm}}
				\toprule
				\textbf{Provider} & \textbf{Models} & \textbf{Type} & \textbf{Est.\ cost (50 cases/day)} \\
				\midrule
				Ollama    & llama3.1:8b, gemma3:4b         & Local  & \$0 / year \\
				OpenAI    & gpt-4o                         & Cloud  & \$180--\$456 / year \\
				Anthropic & claude-3-5-haiku              & Cloud  & \$120--\$300 / year \\
				Groq      & llama-3.3-70b-versatile        & Cloud  & $\approx$\$0--\$20 / year \\
				Google    & gemini-2.0-flash-exp           & Cloud  & $\approx$\$0--\$50 / year \\
				\bottomrule
			\end{tabular}
		}
	\end{table}
	
	
	\paragraph{Prompt Engineering.}
	The prompt is structured in four parts:\\ (1)~a system role definition establishing the model
	as a cautious dental specialist; \\(2)~patient demographics and up to three recent clinical
	notes retrieved from PostgreSQL, providing longitudinal context absent from the radiograph
	alone; \\
	(3)~structured vision findings with confidence scores; and \\
	(4)~retrieved guideline
	passages numbered with source page references. The model is instructed to output JSON
	containing a primary diagnosis (with explicit tooth number), differential diagnoses,
	recommended management steps, and reference page numbers.
	
	A reinforcement instruction is injected when a focus tooth is provided to prevent the
	common failure mode of generating a plausible but incorrectly numbered diagnosis, for
	example: \textit{``CRITICAL: The diagnosis MUST reference tooth \#47. Do NOT diagnose a
		different tooth number.''} Figure~\ref{fig:prompt_structure} illustrates the complete prompt template build up.
	
	\begin{figure}[H]
		\centering
		\includegraphics[width=0.78\textwidth]{figures/fig_prompt_structure.png}
		\caption{Prompt structure used by the clinical reasoning module. The four-part template combines patient context, radiographic findings, retrieved guideline passages with page
			numbers, and a structured JSON output instruction with explicit tooth-number
			enforcement.}
		\label{fig:prompt_structure}
	\end{figure}
	
	Output parsing uses regex-based JSON extraction with schema validation and a plain-text
	fallback for non compliant responses. Page numbers in the model's output are validated
	against the set of pages present in the retrieved chunks, preventing citation of
	non retrieved pages.
	
	% ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
	\subsection{Orchestration Layer and Deterministic Validation}
	\label{sec:orchestration}
	% ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
	
	\texttt{CDSSFusionEngine} coordinates the end to end workflow and enforces clinical
	consistency through the deterministic \texttt{ToothValidator}. This follows the
	safety monitoring pattern for ML
	systems~\cite{safety_monitor_ml_perception, amlas_safety_assurance}, where learned model
	outputs are checked against explicit constraints before downstream use. All corrections
	applied by the validator are logged with their rationale, providing a transparent audit
	trail for clinical oversight.
	
	\paragraph{Deterministic Tooth Validation.}
	Five rules are enforced independently of any AI model (Table~\ref{tab:tooth_validator}).
	These rules encode anatomical facts about periapical radiographs that are not learnable
	from data and represent the first layer of the system's defence-in-depth safety design.
	
	\begin{table}[H]
		\centering
		\caption{Deterministic tooth validation rules in \texttt{ToothValidator}.}
		\label{tab:tooth_validator}
		{\small
			\begin{tabular}{p{3.0cm}p{5.0cm}p{3.8cm}}
				\toprule
				\textbf{Rule} & \textbf{Condition checked} & \textbf{Correction applied} \\
				\midrule
				Quadrant consistency
				& All visible teeth must be in the same FDI quadrant as the focus tooth
				& Remove cross-quadrant teeth \\[3pt]
				Periapical count
				& Maximum 5 teeth visible in one periapical view
				& Retain 3 teeth closest to focus tooth \\[3pt]
				Focus alignment
				& Vision model's \texttt{focused\_tooth} must match the requested tooth
				& Correct to requested tooth \\[3pt]
				Diagnosis inclusion
				& Final diagnosis text must reference the focus tooth number
				& Append tooth number if absent \\[3pt]
				Numbering consistency
				& All tooth numbers must use the same system (FDI vs.\ Universal)
				& Standardise to FDI throughout \\
				\bottomrule
			\end{tabular}
		}
	\end{table}
	
	\paragraph{Final Confidence Scoring.}
	A composite confidence score aggregates evidence from multiple sources
	(Table~\ref{tab:confidence}). The weighted sum yields a score in $[0,1]$, mapped to three
	levels: high ($\geq 0.75$), medium ($\geq 0.45$), low ($< 0.45$). This level is returned
	in every API response, enabling the clinical interface to prompt for specialist review when
	confidence is low.
	
	
	\begin{table}[H]
		\centering
		\caption{Composite confidence score factors in \texttt{CDSSFusionEngine}.}
		\label{tab:confidence}
		\begin{tabular}{lll}
			\toprule
			\textbf{Factor} & \textbf{Weight} & \textbf{Source} \\
			\midrule
			Image quality score       & 0.25 & Vision model self-report \\
			Diagnostic confidence     & 0.30 & Vision model self-report \\
			Knowledge availability    & 0.25 & Retrieved chunk count ($\geq$5\,$\rightarrow$\,1.0; $\geq$1\,$\rightarrow$\,0.5) \\
			Clinical context richness & 0.10 & Presence of clinical notes and tooth number \\
			Findings consistency      & 0.10 & Pathology--retrieval term alignment \\
			\bottomrule
		\end{tabular}
	\end{table}
	
	
	\paragraph{Error Handling and Graceful Degradation.}
	Without a radiograph the pipeline continues in text-only mode with an explicit notation.
	If retrieval returns no chunks above the similarity threshold, the LLM is informed
	explicitly rather than hallucinating guideline content. If an LLM API call fails, a
	structured error response is returned with an advisory to consult a supervising dentist.
	Configurable exponential backoff is applied to transient failures before switching
	providers.
	
	% ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
	\section{Data Flow and Diagnostic Workflow}
	\label{sec:workflow}
	% ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
	
	Figure~\ref{fig:dataflow} illustrates the complete end-to-end data flow for a clinical
	case. A clinician submits a patient ID, chief complaint, optional tooth number, and an
	optional radiograph to \texttt{POST /api/cdss/provide\_final\_recommendation}.
	The \texttt{CDSSFusionEngine} executes the following steps:
	
	\begin{enumerate}
		\item \textbf{Patient data retrieval.} Demographics and up to three recent clinical notes
		are fetched from PostgreSQL, providing longitudinal clinical context.
		\item \textbf{Vision analysis.} The radiograph is preprocessed and submitted to the
		configured vision model, returning structured JSON findings.
		\item \textbf{Knowledge retrieval.} A pathology-specific query is constructed from the
		vision findings and used to retrieve the top-$k$ guideline passages from ChromaDB,
		each carrying its source page number.
		\item \textbf{LLM generation.} Patient context, vision findings, and retrieved passages
		are assembled into the structured four-part prompt and submitted to the configured LLM,
		which returns JSON containing diagnosis, differentials, management, and page citations.
		\item \textbf{Validation and response assembly.} \texttt{ToothValidator} checks and
		corrects the output. The complete \texttt{CDSSResponse} diagnosis, differentials,
		management plan, page citations, confidence metadata, model provenance, and processing
		latency is returned to the API client.
	\end{enumerate}
	
	Processing metadata (model names, inference latency, token counts, and operational cost)
	is collected at each step and exposed through the evaluation dashboard described in
	Chapter~4.
	
\begin{figure}[h]
	\centering
