	\section{Multi-Provider Integration Strategy}
	\label{sec:multi_provider}
	% ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
	
	A central architectural contribution of this work is the systematic abstraction of model
	providers, enabling flexible deployment optimisation for resource constrained settings.
	Both the vision and LLM layers implement the same three part pattern: (i)~a
	provider-agnostic interface that the orchestration engine uses exclusively; (ii)~a factory
	that instantiates the correct client from configuration; and (iii)~lazy-loaded module-level
	singletons that minimise startup overhead.
	
	All provider choices are controlled through environment variables in \texttt{visionconfig.py}
	and \texttt{ragconfig.py}, and can be switched at runtime via the configuration API
	(\texttt{POST: '/api/vision/config'} \& \texttt{'/api/rag/config}') without restarting the
	application. This is critical for the comparative evaluation in Chapter~5, where multiple
	model combinations are tested against the same clinical cases. Figure~\ref{fig:multi_provider}
	illustrates the abstraction architecture.
	
	\begin{figure}[H]
		\centering
		\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{figures/fig_multi_provider.png}
		\caption{Multi-provider abstraction layer. Configuration files drive the
			\texttt{VisionClient} and LLM provider factories at runtime, supporting local (Ollama),
			cloud API strategies without code modification.}
		\label{fig:multi_provider}
	\end{figure}
	
	
	This design directly enables the three-tier deployment model for Tanzania's healthcare
	infrastructure (Table~\ref{tab:deployment_tiers}). In the hybrid district-hospital tier,
	confidence based routing strategy can be applied as a policy: if the local model returns an overall
	confidence below a configurable threshold and internet connectivity is available, the
	request is automatically re-analysed by a cloud provider.
	
