\subsection{Backend API}
\label{subsec:backend}

The backend is implemented using FastAPI~(v0.128+) running on a Uvicorn
ASGI server.  FastAPI was selected for its native async support,
automatic OpenAPI documentation generation, and Pydantic-based
request/response validation, which aligns with the structured JSON
schema approach described in Chapter~\ref{chap:design}.  The application is
organised into modular router groups corresponding to the six API
functional groups described in Chapter~\ref{chap:design}: authentication,
practice management, vision analysis, CDSS, RAG, and cost/evaluation.
A lifespan context manager logs the active configuration at startup---including
vision provider and model name, embedding model and vector store
parameters, LLM provider and model name, and RAG parameters (chunk
size, retrieval strategy, $k$ values)---providing immediate visibility
into the current system configuration for reproducibility across
experimental runs.

\subsection{Relational Database}
\label{subsec:db}

PostgreSQL serves as the relational store for structured clinical data.
SQLAlchemy~2.0 with asyncpg provides the async ORM layer, and Alembic
manages schema migrations.  The schema implements nine tables including
\texttt{users}, \texttt{facilities}, \texttt{patients},
\texttt{encounters}, \texttt{clinical\_notes}, \texttt{diagnoses},
\texttt{prescriptions}, \texttt{appointments}, and \texttt{tokens}.  The
\texttt{clinical\_notes} table is the most operationally significant for
the CDSS pipeline: when a clinical request arrives, the
\texttt{CDSSFusionEngine} fetches the three most recent SOAP notes for
the patient, providing longitudinal context that is absent from the
radiograph alone.

\subsection{Vector Store and Embedding Infrastructure}
\label{subsec:vector}

ChromaDB~(v1.4.1) is used as the persistent vector store for semantic
retrieval of clinical guideline passages.  The langchain-chroma
integration provides a LangChain-compatible retriever interface.
Embeddings are generated by one of two configurable providers: Ollama
(default model: nomic-embed-text) for fully local operation, or
HuggingFace sentence-transformers (alternatives: mxbai-embed-large,
neuml/pubmedbert-base-embeddings) for biomedically-specialised
representations.  The vector store is persisted to disk in the
\texttt{chroma\_db/} directory, enabling reuse across sessions without
re-ingestion.  Retrieval uses Maximal Marginal Relevance (MMR) with
$k{=}8$, $\mathit{fetch\_k}{=}20$, and $\lambda{=}1.0$.  A similarity
threshold of~0.6 is configured but not applied at retrieval time in the
current implementation, so all top-$k$ candidates are returned
regardless of absolute score.

\subsection{Multi-Provider Model Infrastructure}
\label{subsec:providers}

The multi-provider abstraction described in Chapter~\ref{chap:design} is implemented
through two independent configuration modules: \texttt{visionconfig.py}
(controlling the \texttt{VisionClient}) and \texttt{ragconfig.py}
(controlling LLM provider and embedding selection).  All provider
credentials and model selections are read from environment variables via
a \texttt{.env} file.  The configuration is hot-reloadable at runtime
via \texttt{POST /api/vision/config} and \texttt{POST /api/rag/config},
which is essential for the comparative evaluation described in
Section~\ref{sec:eval_method}.  Device selection for local models uses
PyTorch to auto-detect CUDA, MPS~(Apple Silicon), or CPU at startup.

\subsection{Hardware Environment}
\label{subsec:hardware}

All local-model experiments were conducted on a single developer
workstation running macOS with an Apple M-series processor (CPU
inference only, no discrete GPU), 16\,GB unified memory, and SSD
storage.  This configuration was intentional: it mirrors the
\textit{recommended} hardware tier (16\,GB RAM) and the
\textit{minimal} tier (8\,GB RAM) identified as realistic for Tanzania
district-hospital and rural-clinic deployments respectively.  Cloud
model calls were made over a standard broadband connection with typical
round-trip latency of 50--150\,ms to provider endpoints.  Local models
were served via Ollama running on the same machine.

\subsection{Frontend Interface}
\label{subsec:frontend}

A Next.js-based frontend (TypeScript) provides the clinical web
interface, exposing the full practice management workflow patient
registration, encounter creation, clinical notes, prescriptions, and
appointments and integrating with the vision analysis and CDSS
endpoints.  The real time evaluation dashboard, accessible via the
\texttt{/api/evaluation} endpoints, visualises per-model inference
latency, resource utilisation, and cost metrics across experimental
runs, serving as the primary instrument for the comparative model
evaluation in Section~\ref{sec:eval_method}.

