No ground-truth diagnostic labels are available for these images.
Evaluation is therefore model-comparative and case-study based rather
than large-scale supervised-metric based.  Traditional classification
metrics (precision, recall, F1) are not reported.

\subsection{Image Preprocessing Pipeline}
\label{subsec:preproc}

All radiographs undergo standardised preprocessing via the
\texttt{ImageProcessor} class prior to submission to any vision model.
The pipeline executes four steps in sequence:

\begin{enumerate}
  \item \textbf{Format validation}: only JPEG, PNG, and WebP files are
        accepted; all other formats are rejected with an informative
        error.
  \item \textbf{Colour normalisation}: images are converted to RGB,
        handling DICOM-derived greyscale and RGBA inputs.
  \item \textbf{Aspect-preserving resize}: images whose largest
        dimension exceeds 1,024 px are scaled down proportionally;
        smaller images are not upscaled.
  \item \textbf{Optional contrast enhancement}: CLAHE-equivalent
        enhancement via PIL \texttt{ImageEnhance} is available for
        under-exposed films common in resource-constrained settings,
        but disabled by default to avoid modifying image content.
\end{enumerate}

The preprocessing logic is provider-agnostic: all eleven vision models
receive identically preprocessed images, ensuring fair comparison.

\subsection{Knowledge Base Construction}
\label{subsec:kb}

The RAG knowledge base is constructed from two primary document sources:

\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Tanzania Standard Treatment Guidelines (STG-2021)}: a
        618-page PDF published by the Ministry of Health of
        Tanzania, covering diagnostic criteria, drug
        formulary entries, and clinical management pathways for oral
        health conditions.  This is the primary regional clinical
        reference.
  \item \textbf{WHO Oral Health Guidelines}:
        supplementary international guidance used where the Tanzania STG
        does not address a specific condition or procedure.
\end{itemize}

The ingestion pipeline applies four steps to each document:
(1)~\textbf{PDF loading} via PyPDFLoader, preserving page-number
metadata on every text segment; (2)~\textbf{chunking} with
\texttt{RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter} at 1\,500 characters and
100-character overlap; (3)~\textbf{embedding} with the configured model
(default: nomic-embed-text via Ollama); and (4)~\textbf{indexing} into
ChromaDB with source document name, page number, and chunk index stored
as metadata.  The Tanzania STG yields approximately 1\,200--1\,400
chunks.  Embedding and indexing time is approximately 10--15~minutes on
CPU; the resulting collection occupies approximately 150--200\,MB on
disk, well within the storage constraints of all three Tanzania
deployment tiers.  Page-number metadata is subsequently used by the
reasoning module to validate and expose citations in the
\texttt{CDSSResponse}.  Table~\ref{tab:kb} summarises the default
knowledge base characteristics.

