All VLM-based models are prompted to return a standardised JSON schema
containing: \texttt{teeth\_visible}, \texttt{focused\_tooth},
\texttt{caries} (present, location, severity),
\texttt{periapical\_pathology} (present, location, size\_mm,
characteristics), \texttt{bone\_loss}, \texttt{root\_canal\_treatment},
\texttt{restorations}, \texttt{other\_abnormalities},
\texttt{primary\_finding}, \texttt{severity}, \texttt{urgency},
\texttt{image\_quality\_score}, and \texttt{diagnostic\_confidence}.  A
regex-based fallback parser recovers outputs that include markdown fences
or minor schema deviations.  Smaller Ollama-based models (4B and 7B)
receive explicit few-shot schema examples in the prompt to improve JSON
compliance.

BiomedCLIP returns an eight-class probability distribution over dental
pathology categories (dental caries, periapical abscess, periodontal
bone loss, normal tooth, root canal treatment, dental restoration,
impacted tooth, tooth fracture) rather than spatial findings.
Florence-2 generates a free-text caption from which structured findings
are extracted; during experiments it consistently returned
\texttt{structured\_findings~= null} and described radiographs as showing
a healthy tooth, confirming its unsuitability for dental CDSS.

For Ollama-based models, images are base64-encoded and submitted to the
local REST~API at \texttt{http://localhost:11434}.  For cloud models,
the respective Python SDKs are used with identical prompts and schema
instructions.  Provider switching is transparent to the orchestration
layer: the \texttt{VisionClient} factory dispatches based on the
\texttt{VISION\_MODEL\_PROVIDER} environment variable, changeable at
runtime via \texttt{POST /api/vision/config}.

\subsection{RAG Pipeline Implementation}
\label{subsec:rag_impl}

The RAG pipeline is implemented in \texttt{app/RAGsystem/} and managed
by the \texttt{RetrieverFactory} class.  Document ingestion is handled
by a dedicated script (\texttt{scripts/ingest\_documents.py}), which
can be run manually against PDFs placed in the \texttt{documents/}
directory or triggered via the \texttt{POST /api/rag/upload\_document}
endpoint.  Once the ChromaDB collection is persisted at
\texttt{PERSIST\_DIR}, subsequent system restarts load the existing
index directly, reducing startup time to under five seconds.

The retrieval query is constructed programmatically by the
\texttt{CDSSFusionEngine} from the structured vision findings:
identified pathology codes (e.g., \texttt{periapical\_pathology},
\texttt{caries}, \texttt{bone\_loss}) and the focus tooth number are
combined into a targeted natural-language query such as \textit{``moderate
dental caries periapical pathology tooth~47''}.  Using the vision
model's full narrative summary as the retrieval query was deliberately
avoided, as model-generated narrative text may contain artefacts or
imprecise terminology that reduce retrieval precision.

Retrieved chunks are injected into the LLM prompt with explicit page
markers (e.g., \verb|[GUIDELINE p. 43]|), and the LLM is instructed to
cite only page numbers drawn from the provided passages.  Page citations
in the \texttt{CDSSResponse} are cross-checked against the retrieved
chunk set before inclusion, flagging any reference to a non-retrieved
page as a hallucinated citation.

Each RAG response returns the generated answer alongside raw retrieved
chunks logged as \texttt{knowledge\_sources} with fields
\texttt{content}, \texttt{pages}, \texttt{relevance\_score}, and
\texttt{source}.  The structured output schema includes:
\texttt{diagnosis}, \texttt{differential\_diagnoses},
\texttt{recommended\_management} (with \texttt{pharmacological} and
\texttt{non\_pharmacological} sub-fields carrying drug name, dose,
frequency, and \texttt{reference\_page}), \texttt{precautions},
\texttt{reference\_pages}, \texttt{retrieval\_strategy},
\texttt{llm\_provider}, and \texttt{model\_used}.

Across all five LLM providers tested, the toothache query consistently retrieved Tan-
zania STG (2021) pages 383, 384, 385, 387, and 392, confirming stable and reproducible retrieval
behaviour. The “difficulty opening mouth” scenario consistently retrieved pages 383, 387,
401, 532, 392, 358, 531, and 387.

\subsection{Clinical Reasoning and Orchestration}
\label{subsec:cdss_impl}

The \texttt{CDSSFusionEngine} (\texttt{app/cdss\_engine/fusion\_engine.py})
assembles a four-part prompt at inference time: (1)~a system role
definition; (2)~patient demographics and up to three recent SOAP notes
from PostgreSQL; (3)~the structured JSON vision findings with confidence
scores; and (4)~the retrieved guideline passages numbered with source
page references.  When a focus tooth number is provided, a reinforcement
instruction is appended to prevent cross-tooth hallucination.

LLM generation uses temperature $= 0.0$ for deterministic outputs, a
maximum of 1\,500 output tokens, and forced JSON output mode where
supported by the provider.  The \texttt{ToothValidator} enforces five
deterministic rules post-generation: (1)~all visible teeth must be in
the same FDI quadrant as the focus tooth; (2)~tooth count must not
exceed the periapical-view limit; (3)~the diagnosis text must
explicitly reference the focus tooth number; (4)~the vision model's
own \texttt{focused\_tooth} field must match the requested focus; and
(5)~FDI and Universal numbering must not be mixed across fields.
Conservative corrections are applied where possible and recorded in the
structured output.

The image-free pathway
(\texttt{POST /api/cdss/recommendation\_without\_radiograph}) follows
the same orchestration but skips the vision stage and automatically sets
\texttt{confidence\_level} to \texttt{low}, signalling to the clinician
that the recommendation is based on patient history and guideline
retrieval alone.  This pathway represents the baseline condition for
settings where a radiograph is unavailable.


     \subsection{Evaluation and Cost Infrastructure}
     \label{subsec:eval_infra}
    
     Evaluation metrics are collected at each pipeline stage and persisted
     to \texttt{evaluation\_results.json}. The
     \texttt{GET /api/evaluation/dashboard} endpoint consolidates per-model
     inference latency, token throughput (\texttt{tokens\_per\_second}), peak RAM
     usage,
     self-reported confidence scores, and schema validity. The
     \texttt{citation\_count}
     field in \texttt{evaluation\_results.json} shows zero for all vision model tests
    because citations are only populated during the full CDSS pipeline
    (Stage~3), not during the isolated vision analysis stage. The cost
    infrastructure (\texttt{app/shared/}) computes projected costs per 1,000 images
    and requests using provider pricing as of February~2026 multiplied by
    estimated token counts, and encodes three Tanzania deployment scenarios.
   
    The \texttt{cost\_usd} field in \texttt{evaluation\_results.json} reflects
    the estimated API expenditure for cloud-based models (such as GPT-4o and
    Claude 3.5 Sonnet) based on actual token usage and current pricing, while
    local models (e.g., Gemma 3, LLaVA) correctly report \$0.00 in operational
    costs. This ensures that the evaluation data remains consistent with the
    \texttt{/api/cost/} endpoints, which apply published pricing rates to
    simulated deployment scenarios independently of any provider free-tier

