\section{Evaluation Methodology}
\label{sec:eval_method}
% ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Evaluation is primarily system-level and comparative, designed to assess deployment suitability rather than ground-truth classification accuracy. Since expert-labelled ground truth is unavailable for the test radiographs, traditional supervised metrics (precision, recall, F1) are not applicable. The framework instead addresses five dimensions aligned with the research questions in Section ~\ref{sec:objectives}.

\subsection{Evaluation Dimensions}
\label{subsec:dimensions}

The evaluation is organised across five dimensions, each addressing a
distinct research question from Section~\ref{sec:objectives}:

\begin{enumerate}
  \item \textbf{Vision model comparative analysis~(RQ2)}: all eleven
        models benchmarked via \texttt{POST /api/vision/test\_vision\_models}, and individual \texttt{POST /api/vision/analyze\_image} calls,
        isolating vision-layer performance.
  \item \textbf{RAG retrieval quality~(RQ3)}: five LLM providers tested
        via \texttt{POST /api/rag/answer\_question} for citation accuracy,
        response completeness, JSON validity, and dosage accuracy against
        STG pages.
  \item \textbf{End-to-end CDSS evaluation~(RQ3, RQ5)}: four vision+LLM
        combinations tested via the full recommendation endpoint; all
        five LLM providers tested on the image-free pathway.
  \item \textbf{Deployment feasibility analysis~(RQ4)}: three Tanzania
        infrastructure tiers costed using \texttt{/api/cost/} endpoints,
        with hardware requirements and annual operational costs estimated
        per tier.
  \item \textbf{Qualitative clinical utility~(RQ5)}: structured review
        of \texttt{CDSSResponse} outputs for representative case studies,
        assessed against Tanzania STG content.
\end{enumerate}

