\subsection{Qualitative Evaluation}
\label{subsec:qualitative}

Quantitative metrics alone are insufficient to assess clinical utility
in a safety-critical domain.  Qualitative evaluation is therefore
conducted using a structured review applied to representative case study
outputs.  For each case study, the \texttt{CDSSResponse} is assessed
across four criteria:

\begin{enumerate}
  \item \textbf{Diagnostic appropriateness}: does the primary diagnosis
        reflect the radiographic and clinical findings?  Is the
        differential list clinically plausible?
  \item \textbf{Management plan relevance}: are recommended steps
        consistent with Tanzania STG drug names, dosages, and procedures?
  \item \textbf{Citation accuracy}: do returned page numbers correspond
        to actual STG sections containing content relevant to the
        recommendation?
  \item \textbf{Hallucination indicators}: does the output contain
        clinically implausible claims, fabricated dosages, unsupported
        tooth numbers, or references to non-existent guideline sections?
\end{enumerate}

Representative scenarios evaluated qualitatively are: toothache
diagnosis without radiograph (all LLM providers); tooth~47 periapical
abscess with radiograph (four vision+LLM combinations); and difficulty
opening the mouth suggesting pericoronitis (all providers).
Qualitative results are reported in Chapter~\ref{chap:results}.

No formal ablation comparing RAG-enabled versus RAG-disabled pipelines
was conducted across a large case set; this is acknowledged as a
limitation and a direction for future work.

