\end{table}

Several findings warrant discussion. \textbf{Florence-2} returned
\texttt{structured\_findings: null} in every run and described the radiograph as
showing a healthy tooth with no visible cavities, directly contradicting the
known pathology. This reflects its general captioning design; it is \textbf{not
suitable} for the the proposed CDSS' vision pipeline. \textbf{LLaVA~7B} missed periapical
pathology entirely, a clinically significant gap. \textbf{BiomedCLIP} correctly
ranked caries first (59.8\%) and periapical abscess second (20.4\%), but its
classification-only architecture cannot produce FDI tooth numbers or spatial
findings, limiting it to a complementary triage role rather than a standalone
pipeline component.

Among recommended-tier models, \textbf{LLaVA-Med} and \textbf{LLaVA~13B}
detected both primary pathologies. Groq attributed caries to tooth~\#46 rather
than the focus tooth, illustrating spatial localisation limitations at speed.
\textbf{Gemini} produced the richest output (lesion extent, restoration
descriptions, severity: severe) at the highest self-reported confidence (0.92).
Multiple models reported bone loss not present in ground truth, suggesting
over-sensitivity or detection of normal anatomical variation; formal calibration
against clinician-labelled data would be required to resolve this.

It bears emphasis that all confidence scores are model-intrinsic self-assessments.
They cannot serve as clinical decision thresholds without calibration against
expert ground truth.

