\section{End-to-End CDSS Evaluation}
\label{sec:results_cdss}
% ---------------------------------------------------------------------

Three case studies are presented, selected to illustrate the system under
optimal conditions, degraded vision input, and the image-free pathway.

\subsection{Case Study 1: Full Pipeline --- Accurate Pathology Detection}
\label{subsec:case1}

\textbf{Configuration:} LLaVA~13B (vision) + llama3.1:8b (LLM, RAG enabled).

\textbf{Vision output:} teeth visible [47]; caries present (moderate, crown);
periapical pathology present (tooth~47); bone loss present (moderate vertical);
confidence 0.70.

\textbf{CDSS recommendation:}
\begin{quote}
\textit{Diagnosis:} Periapical abscess on tooth~\#47, with moderate caries and
bone loss between teeth 46 and 48. \\
\textit{Differentials:} Gingivitis, Periodontitis, Osteomyelitis of the jaw. \\
\textit{Management:} (1)~Incision and drainage under local anaesthesia;
(2)~ampicillin + cloxacillin (FDC) 500mg PO 8-hourly for 5~days and
metronidazole 400mg PO 8-hourly for 5~days;
(3)~extraction of tooth~\#47 if root canal treatment is not possible. \\
\textit{Reference pages:} 385, 388. \textit{Confidence:} high.
\end{quote}

The diagnosis and management are consistent with STG-2021 Section~16.3.1.
Drug names, doses, and durations match STG entries. All cited pages appear in
the retrieved chunk set. Osteomyelitis as a differential is appropriate and
sourced from page~388. No hallucinated content was identified.

\subsection{Case Study 2: Degraded Vision Input --- System Resilience}
\label{subsec:case2}

\textbf{Configuration:} Florence-2 (vision, low quality output) + llama3.1:8b (LLM, RAG enabled).

\textbf{Vision output:} \texttt{structured\_findings: null}; narrative: ``tooth
appears to be in good condition, no visible cavities''; image quality score:
0.5; diagnostic confidence: 0.5.

\textbf{CDSS recommendation:}
\begin{quote}
\textit{Diagnosis:} Tooth~\#47 likely affected by a periapical abscess,
inferred from patient history and retrieved knowledge. \\
\textit{Differentials:} Trigeminal neuralgia, chronic orofacial pain. \\
\textit{Management:} Incision and drainage; ampicillin-based antibiotic
regimen; extraction if necessary. \\
\textit{Reference pages:} 385, 395. \textit{Confidence:} medium.
\end{quote}

Despite the vision model's complete failure to detect pathology, the FusionEngine
correctly inferred periapical abscess from the patient complaint and retrieved
STG passages. Confidence was \emph{reduced} to ``medium'', appropriately
signalling lower certainty to the clinician. Differential diagnoses broadened
toward non-dental aetiology, reflecting the absence of visual evidence. This
demonstrates the system's resilience: patient history and RAG retrieval
partially compensate for vision failure, while the confidence mechanism
communicates the limitation transparently.


\subsection{Case Study 3: Hallucination Without RAG}

\textbf{Configuration:} ChromaDB intentionally deleted, Florence-2 vision + llama3.1:8b LLM

\textbf{CDSS Output:}
\begin{quote}
\textbf{Diagnosis:} Tooth \#47 is likely experiencing a dental fracture or crack... \\
\textbf{Differential Diagnoses:} Tooth abscess, dental decay \\
\textbf{Recommended Management:} Order new radiograph, administer analgesics, schedule follow-up \\
\textbf{Reference Pages:} []\\
\textbf{Confidence:} low
\end{quote}

\textbf{Analysis:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Without retrieved knowledge, the LLM defaulted to generic management suggestions
    \item Diagnosis (``dental fracture'') was unsupported by evidence and not grounded in guidelines
    \item No reference pages provided, reducing transparency and verifiability
    \item Demonstrates the critical role of RAG in grounding recommendations
\end{itemize}


\subsection{Case Study 4: Image-Free Pathway --- Pericoronitis}
\label{subsec:case3}

\textbf{Endpoint:} \texttt{POST /api/cdss/recommendation\_without\_radiograph}. \\
\textbf{Input:} Chief complaint ``\emph{Difficulty opening the mouth}'', patient~ID=3,
40-year-old female. No image provided.

All five tested providers (llama3.1:8b, llama3:8b, gemma3:4b, gemini-2.5-flash,
Groq llama-3.3-70b) correctly identified \textbf{pericoronitis of the mandibular
third molar} as the primary diagnosis from page~387. All returned
\texttt{confidence\_level: ``low''} by design, appropriately flagging the absence
of radiographic confirmation.

Observed variations are clinically instructive; \\
\textbf{Tooth numbering
inconsistencies:} Groq identified the tooth as \#8 (Universal numbering);
claude-3-haiku as \#38 (FDI, one quadrant displaced from the expected \#48).
Both were flagged and standardised to FDI by the \texttt{ToothValidator},
confirming its clinical necessity as LLMs do not inherently adhere to a single
numbering system without explicit instruction. \\
\textbf{Safety-relevant
differential:} Groq (llama-3.3-70b) surfaced Ludwig's angina as a
differential, clinically appropriate, since trismus is its earliest presenting
sign, and recommended parallel maxillofacial surgery consultation. This
finding was sourced directly from retrieved page~387, demonstrating that
RAG-grounded reasoning can surface life-threatening differentials beyond the
primary diagnosis.\\
\textbf{Isolated failure:} GPT-4o returned the reasoning
chain entry \textit{``Diagnosis: Unable to generate diagnosis''} despite
receiving the complete eight-chunk context, representing an isolated LLM-level
refusal.




