\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:results_discussion}
% ---------------------------------------------------------------------

\subsection{Research Questions Revisited}

\textbf{RQ1 (Architecture and integration):} The implemented three-stage pipeline (vision analysis~$\rightarrow$ RAG retrieval~$\rightarrow$ LLM reasoning), together with unified JSON schemas, provider-agnostic client abstractions, and deterministic validation, demonstrates that heterogeneous vision models, LLMs, and retrieval components can be composed into a reliable, extensible CDSS. The models can be swapped (e.g., BiomedCLIP vs.\ Llama~3.2-Vision; local vs.\ cloud LLMs) without changing upstream or downstream code, and architectural guards (schema validation, tooth-number validator, citation checking) successfully contain provider-specific failures, thereby satisfying requirements on modularity, clear interface contracts, and robust data-flow orchestration.

\textbf{RQ2 (Vision architecture suitability):} A clear capability hierarchy
emerges. Gemini~2.5 Flash leads on quality and cost-efficiency; Gemma3~4B is
the strongest local model; LLaVA-Med provides the best medical contextualisation
for the recommended tier. LLaVA~7B and Florence-2 are unsuitable for production.
Deterministic validation is necessary to enforce tooth-number consistency across
all model families.

\textbf{RQ3 (RAG grounding and retrieval quality):} The MMR retriever delivers
stable, reproducible page coverage, provider-independent. Six of eight LLM
configurations produced valid, citation-accurate recommendations with zero
hallucinated page numbers. Three JSON failures were correctly caught and surfaced.
High-diversity MMR ($\lambda{=}1.0$) is identified as a minor risk for
adjacent-but-not-primary guideline content.

\textbf{RQ4 (Deployment feasibility):} A zero-cost, offline-capable
configuration exists for rural facilities. Cloud configurations remain affordable
(\$5--17/year) for urban facilities. Hybrid deployment reduces costs by up to
80\% versus cloud-only equivalents.

\textbf{RQ5 (Clinical utility):} The system correctly diagnosed periapical
abscess and pericoronitis across multiple configurations, grounded management
in STG-2021 pharmacological entries, appropriately reduced confidence without
imaging, surfaced Ludwig's angina as a safety-relevant differential, and
maintained transparency through explicit page citations. Qualitative review found
no hallucinated drug dosages or fabricated guideline references in any RAG-enabled
output.

\subsection{Key Insights}

The evaluation surfaces five cross-cutting insights relevant to both system
refinement and future clinical validation:

\begin{enumerate}

\item \textbf{RAG is essential for grounding.} Without retrieved knowledge, the
LLM generates unsupported diagnoses and generic management plans devoid of STG
citations, as demonstrated by the Florence-2 degraded-vision case. RAG retrieval
is the primary mechanism by which hte system achieves guideline adherence and
hallucination control.

\item \textbf{Vision quality propagates through the full pipeline.} LLaVA~7B's
missed periapical finding caused the CDSS to diagnose only mild caries despite
correct retrieval. Florence-2's failure was partially rescued by patient history,
but at the cost of reduced confidence and broader differentials. Cases where vision models failed led to less accurate diagnoses, even with perfect retrieval.

\item \textbf{Local models are clinically viable.} Gemma3~4B and llama3.1:8b,
running on commodity hardware at zero cost, together produce clinically
appropriate, STG-grounded recommendations indistinguishable in structure from
cloud-API outputs. This directly supports the feasibility of rural deployment
in Tanzania without ongoing operational expenditure.

\item \textbf{Deterministic validation adds measurable safety.} The tooth
validator caught numbering inconsistencies in multiple providers, corrected
them without LLM involvement, and logged every correction for audit.
This layer is low-cost to operate and high-value for clinical trust.

\item \textbf{RAG diversity requires tuning.} The $\lambda{=}1.0$ MMR setting
maximises chunk diversity but risks surfacing adjacent guideline content.
Reducing $\lambda$ or adding a similarity threshold would improve query
specificity at the cost of reduced coverage for complex presentations.
This represents a near-term optimisation opportunity.

\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Failure Modes and Limitations}

\paragraph{Vision layer.}
Florence-2 failed pathology detection on all runs; LLaVA~7B missed periapical
pathology; BiomedCLIP cannot localise findings spatially. These are
architecture-level constraints addressed in the deployment recommendations
by model exclusion.

\paragraph{LLM output.}
Both Gemini~2.5 models failed JSON output for the RAG query; GPT-4o produced an isolated image-free reasoning
failure (GPT-4o LLM failed to diagnose in absence of Vision input). Corrective action (Gemini native JSON mode) recommended as near-term implementation tasks.

\paragraph{Tooth numbering.}
LLMs do not inherently adhere to FDI notation. Future prompts should enforce
FDI notation explicitly, and the validator should be extended to detect and
normalise Universal/ISO-3950 variants systematically.

\paragraph{Evaluation scope.}
The evaluation uses a single test radiograph with no expert-labelled ground
truth; consequently, classical classification metrics (precision, recall, AUROC)
cannot be reported. No large-scale RAG ablation study was conducted. Qualitative
review was performed by the researcher rather than independent Tanzanian dental
clinicians. These constitute the primary agenda for future validation work,
elaborated in Chapter~\ref{chap:conclusion}.

