\section{Chapter Summary}
\label{sec:ch5_summary}
% ---------------------------------------------------------------------

This chapter has reported the results of the the CDSS evaluation across five
dimensions, producing the following principal conclusions that directly inform
Chapter~\ref{chap:conclusion}:

\begin{enumerate}

\item \textbf{Vision layer.} Gemma3~4B is the strongest minimal-tier local model
(2.5~GB, \$0, correct detection of both primary pathologies); LLaVA-Med and
LLaVA~13B are viable recommended-tier options; Gemini~2.5 Flash is the optimal
cloud model (0.92 confidence, richest findings, \$5--6/year). Florence-2 and
LLaVA~7B are excluded from production recommendations.

\item \textbf{RAG pipeline.} Six of eight LLM configurations produced valid,
STG-2021-grounded recommendations with zero hallucinated page citations.
Gemini-2.5-flash models and Gemini-2.5-pro failed JSON output. Retrieval was reproducible and provider-independent.

\item \textbf{Clinical case evaluation.} The system correctly diagnosed
periapical abscess and pericoronitis, grounded management in STG-2021 drug
entries, reduced confidence appropriately without imaging, and surfaced
Ludwig's angina as a safety-relevant differential.

\item \textbf{Deployment.} A clear three-tier pathway is established:
Gemma3~4B + llama3.1:8b for offline rural facilities (\$0);
LLaVA-Med + Groq fallback for district hospitals (\$0--11/year);
Gemini~2.5 Flash for referral hospitals (\$5--17/year). Hybrid configurations
reduce costs by up to 80\% versus cloud-only equivalents.

\item \textbf{Limitations.} No expert-labelled ground truth;
no formal large-scale RAG ablation; no independent clinician review. These
constitute the primary future-work agenda.

\end{enumerate}

These findings, together with the identified failure modes and improvement
opportunities, provide the evidentiary basis for the conclusions and future
work directions in Chapter~\ref{chap:conclusion}.


