\chapter{Conclusion and Future Work}
\label{chap:conclusion}

This chapter synthesises the research contributions, draws conclusions from
the evaluation findings, acknowledges the study's limitations, and outlines
directions for future work. It concludes by reflecting on the broader
implications of this research for knowledge-grounded AI systems in dentistry
and other imaging-rich clinical domains.

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Summary of Research Contributions}
\label{sec:conclusion_contributions}
% ---------------------------------------------------------------------

This thesis set out to address a well-defined gap: the absence of trustworthy, guideline-
grounded dental clinical decision support in resource-constrained settings, compounded by
the near-total lack of comprehensively labelled dental radiograph datasets that would oth-
erwise enable supervised fine-tuning. Rather than pursuing model training, the work de-
signed and implemented a RAG-based multimodal CDSS, designed as a modular pipeline
that orchestrates pre-trained vision models, retrieval components, and large language models,
grounding their outputs in the Tanzania Standard Treatment Guidelines 2021 (STG-2021).

The central architectural contribution is a three-stage sequential pipeline
(vision analysis $\rightarrow$ knowledge retrieval $\rightarrow$ clinical
reasoning) with stable REST interface contracts that enable independent component
substitution. Eleven vision models and five LLM providers were tested through
identical API endpoints without changes to surrounding code, demonstrating
modularity in practice. The \texttt{FusionEngine} aggregates heterogeneous
outputs; probability distributions from BiomedCLIP, free-text captions from
Florence-2, structured JSON from VLMs, into a unified response schema; the
deterministic \texttt{ToothValidator} enforces FDI tooth-number consistency as
a stateless post-processing layer independent of any model family. Together,
these design choices produce graceful degradation under component failure
(reduced confidence rather than hard errors) and meet the extensibility
requirements of RQ1.

Beyond the inference pipeline, the software artefact is production-ready: it
includes patient and appointment management, SOAP clinical note storage,
role-based access control, a Next.js frontend, and a real-time evaluation
dashboard. PostgreSQL handles relational clinical records; ChromaDB handles
vector retrieval from the 1,200--1,400-chunk STG-2021 knowledge base. This
full-stack implementation demonstrates that research-grade multimodal AI can be
embedded within a functioning clinical workflow, a practical software engineering
contribution distinct from the architectural one.

The knowledge-base and RAG design operationalises guideline grounding for a
concrete clinical domain: the 618-page STG-2021 was chunked (1,500-character
chunks, 100-character overlap), embedded (Nomic-embed-text), indexed, and
retrieved via MMR ($k{=}8$, $\lambda{=}1.0$). All successful CDSS outputs
include explicit STG page citations, enabling clinician verification at the
source. No hallucinated page numbers appeared in any RAG-enabled response
across all tested scenarios, and drug names, doses, and durations matched
STG-2021 entries exactly. This demonstrates region-specific guideline
integration without model retraining, satisfying RQ3 and RQ4.

The evaluation and deployment contributions address the practical question of
\emph{which models, at what cost, on what hardware}. The multi-model benchmark
(eleven vision models, eight LLM configurations, identical conditions)
produces concrete tradeoffs; Gemma3~4B at \$0 and 26~seconds versus
Gemini~2.5~Flash at \$0.0003 and 16~seconds, versus Florence-2 which fails
entirely, directly actionable for deployment decisions. Three evidence-based
configurations are specified for Tanzania's healthcare tiers: offline rural
clinics (\$0), hybrid district hospitals (\$0--\$11/year), and cloud-first
referral facilities (\$5--\$17/year), with hybrid routing reducing costs by
up to 80\% relative to cloud-only configurations. These design insights, offline-first capability, tiered model selection, zero-cost local operation,
knowledge-base localisation without retraining, are transferable to other
regions and clinical domains facing analogous infrastructure constraints.

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Conclusions}
\label{sec:conclusion_conclusions}
% ---------------------------------------------------------------------

The evaluation results presented in Chapter~\ref{chap:results} support the following conclusions
regarding the research questions formulated in Chapter~\ref{chap:introduction}.

\textbf{RQ1: Architectural Design and Component Integration.}
The three-stage pipeline
successfully decoupled component concerns, enabling eleven vision models and eight LLM
configurations to be tested through identical interfaces without pipeline code changes. The
FusionEngine correctly handled heterogeneous vision outputs, and the ToothValidator con-
tained provider-specific numbering failures without LLM involvement. The system degraded
gracefully under component failure, confirming that the interface contracts and orchestration
design meet the reliability and extensibility requirements of RQ1. Adding a new provider
requires only a new client class and a configuration entry.

\textbf{RQ2: Vision Model Selection and Cost-Performance Tradeoffs.}
A clear capability hierarchy emerged. Gemini~2.5~Flash leads on diagnostic
quality (0.95 confidence, richest structured findings) at \$0.0003/request.
Gemma3~4B is the strongest local model (0.85 confidence, 2.5~GB, \$0, correct
detection of both primary pathologies) and is the recommended choice for
offline rural deployment. LLaVA-Med and LLaVA~13B are viable recommended-tier
options for 16~GB systems. LLaVA~7B and Florence-2 are unsuitable for production
due to missed periapical pathology and null structured outputs respectively.
Model-intrinsic confidence scores are not calibrated against expert ground
truth and cannot serve as clinical thresholds without further validation.

\textbf{RQ3: Retrieval Quality and Evidence Grounding.}
The MMR retriever delivered stable, provider-independent retrieval: identical
chunk sets were returned across all LLM configurations for each test query.
Six of eight LLM configurations returned valid structured JSON with zero
hallucinated page references; all cited pages appeared in the retrieved chunk
set. Drug names, doses, and durations matched STG-2021 entries exactly.
The $\lambda{=}1.0$ diversity setting surfaced adjacent-but-not-primary guideline
content in one case, confirming RAG grounding as effective but identifying
retrieval parameter tuning as an open optimisation task.

\textbf{RQ4: Regional Guideline Integration and Deployment Optimisation.}
The Tanzania STG-2021 was successfully encoded into 1,200--1,400 retrievable
ChromaDB passages with page-level metadata. All successful RAG outputs cited
genuine STG pages, with pharmacological regimens matching guideline entries for
periapical abscess, pericoronitis, and toothache management. A three-tier
deployment pathway is established:
\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Rural clinics:} Gemma3~4B + llama3.1:8b (offline, \$0)
  \item \textbf{District hospitals:} LLaVA-Med + Groq/Gemini fallback (hybrid,
        \$0--\$11/year)
  \item \textbf{Urban facilities:} Gemini~2.5~Flash (cloud-first,
        \$5--\$17/year)
\end{itemize}
These configurations are technically feasible on commodity hardware and
economically sustainable without recurring model licensing costs. The prices are of February 2026.

\textbf{RQ5: System-Level Performance and Clinical Utility.}
The end-to-end system correctly diagnosed periapical abscess and pericoronitis
across multiple configurations, grounded management in STG-2021 pharmacological
entries, appropriately reduced confidence without imaging, and surfaced Ludwig's
angina as a safety-relevant differential. Qualitative review found no hallucinated
drug dosages or fabricated guideline references in any RAG-enabled output. The
deterministic tooth validator corrected FDI numbering inconsistencies across
all test cases with negligible latency. Taken together, these results
confirm that, even without fine-tuning and without comprehensive labelled data,
the system produces guideline-aligned, cited recommendations suitable for use
as an assistive tool by general dental practitioners and interns. The system is
an aid to clinical reasoning, not an autonomous diagnostician; human oversight
is assumed throughout.


\section{Limitations}
\label{sec:limitations}

Several limitations of this research must be acknowledged when interpreting the findings and assessing the generalisability of conclusions:

\textbf{1. Imaging Modality Scope.} The study is limited to periapical radiographs, excluding panoramic radiographs, bitewing images, and cone-beam computed tomography (CBCT). This decision was necessitated by the predominance of usage of periapical radiographs instead of other dental imaging modalities in resource-constrained settings as they are the least expensive imaging technique, yet provide valuable diagnostic value in routine dentistry. System performance should not be assumed to generalise to other imaging modalities without empirical validation.

\textbf{2. Dataset Constraints and Absence of Ground Truth.} Evaluation relies on publicly available datasets rather than proprietary clinical data from Tanzanian healthcare facilities. Patient history data and clinical notes are synthesised for experimental purposes due to privacy and confidentiality restrictions. Critically, \textbf{no ground-truth diagnostic labels are available} for the test radiographs, precluding traditional classification metrics (precision, recall, F1) for many evaluation scenarios.

\textbf{3. The Fundamental Challenge of Dental Data Labelling.} The absence of comprehensively labelled dental datasets is not merely a limitation of this study but a fundamental challenge facing the entire field of dental AI research. Creating such datasets is inherently difficult for several reasons:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Various radiographic modalities:} Dental imaging encompasses multiple modalities; periapical, bitewing, panoramic, and CBCT, each with different anatomical perspectives, resolutions, and diagnostic purposes. A single patient may have multiple image types, and models must learn to interpret each appropriately.

    \item \textbf{Multiple features requiring annotation:} A single radiograph contains numerous anatomical structures and potential pathologies that require labelling: individual teeth (each needing identification and numbering), caries (with location, depth, and surface specification), periapical lesions (size, characteristics, associated tooth), bone loss (type, location, severity), restorations (type, location, condition), root canal treatments, fractures, and other abnormalities. Each finding may be present or absent, and multiple findings often co-exist. Furthermore, clinical plan decision is dependent on conclusions made form these findings

    \item \textbf{Teeth must be individually identified first:} Before any pathology can be localised, each tooth must be correctly identified and numbered according to a standardised system (e.g., FDI). This is non-trivial due to anatomical variations, missing teeth, restorations obscuring anatomy, and overlapping structures. Treatment decisions are tooth-specific, making accurate tooth identification a prerequisite for clinical utility.

    \item \textbf{Diagnostic interpretation is complex:} The same radiographic finding may signify different conditions depending on context. A radiolucency at the root apex could represent a periapical abscess, granuloma, or cyst, with different treatment implications. Differential diagnosis requires integrating multiple visual cues that may be subtle and subjective.

    \item \textbf{Treatment depends on multiple factors:} Management decisions depend not only on the pathology identified but also on tooth restorability, patient symptoms, systemic health, and available resources, information that may not be fully captured in the radiograph alone.

    \item \textbf{Expert annotation is resource-intensive:} Accurate labelling requires experienced dental clinicians, whose time is scarce and expensive. Achieving inter-annotator agreement on subjective findings is challenging, and the scale of annotation required for comprehensive datasets is prohibitive for most research groups.
\end{itemize}

These challenges explain why, despite advances in dental AI, there remains no publicly available dataset that pairs periapical radiographs with comprehensive, expert-verified labels covering all clinically relevant findings for the same patient. This thesis explicitly addresses this gap by proposing a RAG-based approach that does not require comprehensive labelled training data, instead grounding recommendations in retrieved clinical guidelines.

\textbf{4. Use of Pre-trained Models Without Fine-Tuning.} The system exclusively employs pre-trained models without any domain-specific fine-tuning on dental radiographs. While this design choice aligns with the research objective of developing deployable systems without requiring extensive labelled datasets, specialised fine-tuning could potentially improve diagnostic accuracy, particularly for subtle pathologies or rare conditions.

\textbf{5. Absence of RAG Ablation Studies.} The evaluation framework compares different vision models within the RAG-enhanced system but does not include systematic ablation studies isolating the specific contribution of retrieval augmentation versus non-RAG baselines across a large case set. This constrains conclusions about the magnitude of hallucination reduction attributable to RAG.

\textbf{6. Clinical Validation Scope.} Evaluation is primarily technical and system-focused rather than clinical. No large-scale clinical trials involving practicing Tanzanian dentists have been conducted to validate system utility, trustworthiness, or workflow integration. Assessment of diagnostic accuracy relies on proxy measures (model confidence, citation quality) rather than direct comparison to expert consensus.

\textbf{7. Knowledge Base Currency.} The knowledge base represents a static snapshot of the Tanzania STG at the time of system development, without mechanisms for automatic updates as policies evolve. System recommendations are bounded by the currency and coverage of source documents.

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Future Research Directions}
\label{sec:conclusion_future}
% ---------------------------------------------------------------------

The limitations above define a prioritised research agenda.

\subsection{Comprehensive Dental Dataset Construction}

The highest-priority future task is the creation of a publicly available,
multi-centre dental radiograph dataset representative of Tanzanian patient
populations. The labelling protocol must address all four challenges identified:
modality coverage (periapical at minimum, bitewing and panoramic where possible);
tooth-level FDI identification as the first labelling pass; multi-label
pathology annotation per tooth; and treatment decision labels with explicit
rationale distinguishing radiographic from clinical decision factors.
Inter-annotator agreement must be measured and reported. Such a dataset would,
for the first time, enable formal precision/recall evaluation, supervised
fine-tuning of local VLMs on domain-specific data, and ablation studies that
quantify the RAG contribution in controlled terms.

\subsection{Domain-Specific Fine-Tuning and Comparative Evaluation}

Once a labelled dataset is available, domain-specific fine-tuning of the most
promising local models (Gemma3~4B, LLaVA-Med) should be pursued using
parameter-efficient techniques (e.g., LoRA) that respect the hardware constraints
of the target deployment environment. The modular pipeline requires no structural
changes: a fine-tuned vision model replaces its pre-trained counterpart through
the existing provider interface. The key comparative question is whether
fine-tuned models can match RAG-grounded pre-trained models on citation accuracy
and guideline adherence, or whether the combination of fine-tuning and RAG
yields superior results.

\subsection{Formal RAG Ablation and Retrieval Optimisation}

A systematic ablation study should compare RAG-enabled versus RAG-disabled
configurations across a large, diverse set of clinical queries, measuring
hallucination rates, citation accuracy, dosage correctness, and diagnostic
appropriateness. Retrieval parameter optimisation; chunk size, overlap,
$k$, MMR $\lambda$, and similarity thresholds, should be evaluated against
a curated query-to-expected-page gold standard. Hybrid dense-sparse retrieval
and graph-based approaches that support multi-hop reasoning over interconnected
guideline sections should also be explored.

\subsection{Multi-Modality Extension}

Extending the vision layer to panoramic radiographs and bitewing images would
substantially increase clinical scope. Each modality requires a dedicated
preprocessing pipeline and modality-aware prompting strategy; the retrieval
and reasoning layers require no structural changes. CBCT support would
additionally require volumetric image handling and a 3-D compatible schema,
a larger engineering effort that would enable the most diagnostically complete
radiographic assessment.

\subsection{Clinical Validation with Tanzanian Practitioners}

Prospective clinical studies with practising Tanzanian dentists are the
essential next step before any deployment consideration. Such studies should
measure diagnostic agreement between DentoBase outputs and expert consensus,
assess the impact on treatment decisions and STG adherence, investigate
usability and workflow integration, and identify systematic failure cases
not visible in the current single-image evaluation. This work should be
accompanied by early engagement with the Tanzania Medicines and Medical Devices
Authority and relevant ethical review boards, and should include formal bias
evaluation across patient demographic groups.

\subsection{Safety Layer Extensions and EHR Integration}

The deterministic validation layer can be extended beyond tooth-number
consistency to include rule-based safety checks on drug-dose-age combinations,
drug interaction screening, and allergy contraindication checking against the
patient record. Integration with Tanzania's national health information
infrastructure via HL7~FHIR would enable the system to receive structured
patient context directly, reducing manual data entry and improving recommendation
personalisation.

\subsection{Generalisation to Other Clinical Domains}

The modular architecture, RAG grounding mechanism, tiered deployment framework,
and deterministic validation pattern are not dentistry-specific. The pipeline
can be adapted to other imaging-rich specialties; radiology, ophthalmology,
dermatology, and to other low- and middle-income country contexts by
substituting the domain-specific vision model, replacing the knowledge base
with the relevant national treatment guidelines, and extending the validator
with domain-appropriate consistency rules.

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Closing Remarks}
\label{sec:conclusion_closing}
% ---------------------------------------------------------------------

Dental disease affects an estimated 3.5 billion people worldwide, yet dental
expertise is among the most unequally distributed in global health. Tanzania,
with a dentist-to-population ratio of approximately 1:360,000, exemplifies
the challenge facing much of sub-Saharan Africa: the clinical knowledge needed
to diagnose and manage the most prevalent oral conditions is not available at
the point of care for the vast majority of patients.

This thesis has demonstrated that a carefully engineered RAG-based system;
built entirely from open-source components, running on commodity hardware,
without labelled training data or model fine-tuning, can produce
guideline-aligned dental recommendations that cite their sources, calibrate
their confidence to available evidence, and operate without internet connectivity
or ongoing cost. These are not properties of frontier models; they are properties
of \emph{architecture}: of how components are composed and how each infromation collected is carefully selected and fused towards the model's final reasoning, how knowledge is
grounded, and how uncertainty is propagated and communicated.

At the same time, the work has been explicit about what it is not. The system
is a proof of concept, not a clinical tool. No expert
labels, no practitioner validation. The dental dataset problem, structurally
difficult, expensive to solve, and largely unsolved for African patient
populations, remains the primary barrier between the approach demonstrated
here and a system that could support real clinical decisions. Articulating
that problem precisely, and showing that a RAG-based approach can deliver value
in its absence, are themselves contributions this thesis makes to the field.

The path from proof of concept to clinical deployment is long. It requires
dataset construction, fine-tuning experiments, formal ablation, practitioner
studies, regulatory engagement, and safety evaluation. That path is now better
defined. The architecture, the evaluation framework, the deployment analysis,
and the dataset challenge specification presented in this thesis provide a
concrete, reproducible foundation on which that validation work can be built.

	
